00:06:55.030 --> 00:06:57.810
OK, so we got to
the point last time

00:06:57.810 --> 00:07:01.750
around of seeing that,
OK, prenatal effects--

00:07:01.750 --> 00:07:04.460
the last thing we focused on
was the actual nuts and bolts

00:07:04.460 --> 00:07:07.170
of it, epigenetics, all of that.

00:07:07.170 --> 00:07:11.930
Now we transition to what became
the much more modern, exciting

00:07:11.930 --> 00:07:14.370
version of behavior
genetics, unless you happen

00:07:14.370 --> 00:07:15.980
to have yourself
hundreds of pairs

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:18.490
of identical twins
separated at birth, which

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:22.820
is to go and actually find
the gene, finally beginning

00:07:22.820 --> 00:07:27.430
to bring together-- to
marry the classical behavior

00:07:27.430 --> 00:07:31.012
genetics approaches
with molecular biology.

00:07:31.012 --> 00:07:32.470
And it was starting
around the '80s

00:07:32.470 --> 00:07:35.580
or so that people began
to be able to work

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:39.270
in actual molecular techniques
into this whole field,

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:41.920
and it started off in
a very primitive way

00:07:41.920 --> 00:07:44.680
and has gotten much
better since then.

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:46.840
The version that you
can start off with

00:07:46.840 --> 00:07:50.870
is you know something
about the trait,

00:07:50.870 --> 00:07:53.100
or as we're really
saying here, you

00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:55.620
know something about that
there are differences

00:07:55.620 --> 00:07:58.090
in the trait among
different individuals,

00:07:58.090 --> 00:08:00.690
and now you go
looking for the gene.

00:08:00.690 --> 00:08:02.560
How do you do that?

00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:04.590
The first classical
way of doing that

00:08:04.590 --> 00:08:07.820
is that you actually have
an observable difference

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:11.300
in two individuals,
in two populations,

00:08:11.300 --> 00:08:13.770
in two branches of
the same family,

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:17.500
a difference in an external
manifestation of what's

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:19.130
going on with
genes, a difference

00:08:19.130 --> 00:08:23.490
in phenotype-- appearance,
behavior, some such thing.

00:08:23.490 --> 00:08:26.290
And what you then do is
you use that approach

00:08:26.290 --> 00:08:29.630
to try to then find
genetic differences.

00:08:29.630 --> 00:08:31.490
You get a whole
bunch of examples

00:08:31.490 --> 00:08:34.100
of folks with one version,
a whole bunch of folks

00:08:34.100 --> 00:08:36.679
with another version,
and you start looking

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:38.850
for where the differences are.

00:08:38.850 --> 00:08:41.020
Slightly more
constrained version,

00:08:41.020 --> 00:08:43.549
you don't actually
have the phenotype.

00:08:43.549 --> 00:08:46.220
You are not looking
at eye color.

00:08:46.220 --> 00:08:49.410
You are not looking at how
wrinkly somebody's face is.

00:08:49.410 --> 00:08:52.940
You are not looking
at behavioral traits.

00:08:52.940 --> 00:08:55.140
You're not looking
at anything external.

00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:58.120
The next more
focused step is now,

00:08:58.120 --> 00:09:02.650
you're looking at proteins,
what some proteins do.

00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:07.110
Here is some enzyme that
turns this into that,

00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:10.190
and there's two different
ways the enzyme can do it

00:09:10.190 --> 00:09:12.060
or two different variants on it.

00:09:12.060 --> 00:09:14.522
And now, we've got
this bunch of people

00:09:14.522 --> 00:09:15.980
where we take their
blood and look,

00:09:15.980 --> 00:09:17.430
and they've got this variant.

00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:20.780
These guys have this version
of how the protein goes

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:22.180
about its business.

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:24.990
Can we find the
genetic difference?

00:09:24.990 --> 00:09:27.750
Next step down, next
step more frustrating--

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:30.970
when you can't see
external differences

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:32.190
that you're tracking.

00:09:32.190 --> 00:09:33.810
There is no
phenotypic difference

00:09:33.810 --> 00:09:35.870
that you've got to
work with, where

00:09:35.870 --> 00:09:39.510
you don't know what the protein
does, what its function is.

00:09:39.510 --> 00:09:43.660
Next, lower rent version is to
look at the same protein that

00:09:43.660 --> 00:09:46.930
comes in slightly
different sizes

00:09:46.930 --> 00:09:49.310
because that's usually
a hint that there

00:09:49.310 --> 00:09:50.580
are different functions.

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:53.350
The way the protein
works is going to differ,

00:09:53.350 --> 00:09:55.670
and somewhere along
the way there,

00:09:55.670 --> 00:09:58.520
you came up with one
version by having

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:02.020
some insertion, mutation, or
deletion, or some such thing.

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:03.776
You don't know what
the protein does,

00:10:03.776 --> 00:10:05.150
and you certainly
don't know what

00:10:05.150 --> 00:10:07.520
that does in terms of the
individual's appearance,

00:10:07.520 --> 00:10:10.510
behavior phenotype, but at
least you've got something

00:10:10.510 --> 00:10:12.440
to work with there.

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:15.990
So what it is you are using as
your starting point-- easiest

00:10:15.990 --> 00:10:17.450
external signs.

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:21.420
Next is what would be called
intermediate physiological

00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:22.310
endpoints.

00:10:22.310 --> 00:10:24.800
Intermediate-- it's
something functional,

00:10:24.800 --> 00:10:27.370
but it's not functional like
how the person functions.

00:10:27.370 --> 00:10:30.600
It's functional like how an
individual protein functions.

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:33.470
And then, if you're up the
creek with that, at least

00:10:33.470 --> 00:10:37.810
hopefully going for differences
in the size of the protein,

00:10:37.810 --> 00:10:40.650
the electrical charge
of the protein.

00:10:40.650 --> 00:10:44.250
For non-chemistry types, how
this version of the protein

00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:46.880
interacts with a
water environment

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:48.930
versus how that
version-- you don't

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:51.000
know what the protein
does, but at least

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:52.700
you've got something
to work with.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:54.370
You got a difference.

00:10:54.370 --> 00:10:56.650
In all of these
cases, the strategy

00:10:56.650 --> 00:10:59.680
is to then see what are
the gene differences that

00:10:59.680 --> 00:11:00.970
go along with it?

00:11:00.970 --> 00:11:05.270
Primitive initial version
would be as follows.

00:11:05.270 --> 00:11:07.060
You've got, for
example-- in this case,

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:11.640
you were trying to find
the gene for some disease.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:13.180
And this is where
the whole field

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:17.460
started because it is a lot
easier to go after a disease.

00:11:17.460 --> 00:11:19.750
Either you have it
or you don't if you

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:21.960
pick the right kind
of awful disease,

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:26.510
rather than going on a
phenotype like television taste.

00:11:26.510 --> 00:11:29.090
That one's going to be a lot
harder to find the gene for.

00:11:29.090 --> 00:11:33.620
The whole field started instead
looking at extremes of really

00:11:33.620 --> 00:11:36.350
major league,
you-got-it-or-you-don't-have-it

00:11:36.350 --> 00:11:37.460
diseases.

00:11:37.460 --> 00:11:40.603
So you've got this family
that has this disease running

00:11:40.603 --> 00:11:45.090
in the family-- PKU,
phenylketonuria, for example,

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:49.160
or Huntington's disease,
or cystic fibrosis.

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:51.180
These were some of
the first ones to go.

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:53.580
And what you now do is
you've got the big family,

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:57.390
and what you want ideally is
a big huge family where about

00:11:57.390 --> 00:12:02.670
half the people have the
disease and half don't.

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:05.160
And the initial way the
whole approach would be done

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:07.690
was you get blood samples
from everybody there,

00:12:07.690 --> 00:12:10.770
and you start sifting
through everybody's DNA,

00:12:10.770 --> 00:12:12.800
and you're looking
for a stretch of DNA

00:12:12.800 --> 00:12:16.110
that everybody with a
disease has in common

00:12:16.110 --> 00:12:20.080
and that none of the relatives
without the disease have.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:21.670
And what you've
got at that point

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:25.820
is what would be called a
genetic marker because doing

00:12:25.820 --> 00:12:29.400
it this way, you're just
sifting through a haystack.

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:32.240
You're just trying to pick
up big, crude patterns.

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:35.650
The difference that you wind
up seeing between these two

00:12:35.650 --> 00:12:38.970
populations of relatives
almost certainly-- in fact,

00:12:38.970 --> 00:12:41.490
as far as I know, never
once with this approach

00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:44.520
had you just found
the individual gene.

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:46.600
You found a stretch
of DNA that's

00:12:46.600 --> 00:12:49.030
got 10, 20, 30 genes in there.

00:12:49.030 --> 00:12:52.530
But somewhere in that stretch
is the interesting one.

00:12:52.530 --> 00:12:55.700
So at least you have
a genetic marker here.

00:12:55.700 --> 00:12:57.890
You know the
genetic neighborhood

00:12:57.890 --> 00:13:00.040
where the difference occurs.

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:03.190
So this was at one
point cutting edge,

00:13:03.190 --> 00:13:06.420
a technique called RFLP,
restriction fragment link

00:13:06.420 --> 00:13:07.360
polymorphisms.

00:13:07.360 --> 00:13:08.760
Do not write that down.

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:11.280
And this technique
was incredibly

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:15.670
slick at some point early
on, and it is not easily done

00:13:15.670 --> 00:13:20.930
because you are dumping
20,000 puzzle pieces over here

00:13:20.930 --> 00:13:22.960
and 20,000 there,
and you're looking

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:24.760
for the one difference
between the two

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:26.390
that's otherwise identical.

00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:28.160
It's that sort of task.

00:13:28.160 --> 00:13:29.990
Nonetheless, using
that approach,

00:13:29.990 --> 00:13:32.900
people began to
get disease markers

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:36.360
where they got the stretch
of DNA that contained

00:13:36.360 --> 00:13:38.740
a whole bunch of genes
and who knows what else,

00:13:38.740 --> 00:13:41.180
but at least the
candidate gene, the gene

00:13:41.180 --> 00:13:43.020
that was floating
around that was

00:13:43.020 --> 00:13:45.930
responsible for this
disease, was somewhere

00:13:45.930 --> 00:13:48.260
in the stretch of DNA.

00:13:48.260 --> 00:13:51.790
At that point, what would be
done is a number of things.

00:13:51.790 --> 00:13:55.340
First is people would
obsessively, obsessively check

00:13:55.340 --> 00:13:59.800
their statistics to see just
how certain they are that this

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:02.240
is the genetic marker
for this disease

00:14:02.240 --> 00:14:04.910
because you were soon
going to be advising people

00:14:04.910 --> 00:14:07.760
whether to terminate
pregnancies based

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:09.640
on genetic tests like those.

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:14.260
This is an area where more
stringent rules were imposed

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:17.390
before you announce you think
you know how the universe works

00:14:17.390 --> 00:14:19.140
with respect to this disease.

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:21.920
Really, really major
room for things

00:14:21.920 --> 00:14:25.540
going wrong in terms of it
being then applied clinically,

00:14:25.540 --> 00:14:28.550
so first big demand
would be you really

00:14:28.550 --> 00:14:31.590
have to be much more certain--
a much more demanding field

00:14:31.590 --> 00:14:33.840
than lots of others in biology.

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:38.980
The next issue would be
this bioethics problem,

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:41.080
which is you've got
somebody from one

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:44.510
of these families who may
or may not have the disease.

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:47.840
This is a disease that doesn't
get you until age whatever,

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:51.520
and you're younger than
that, and this immediately

00:14:51.520 --> 00:14:54.330
exploded this whole
issue for the first time.

00:14:54.330 --> 00:14:57.050
Should people get
tested if they have

00:14:57.050 --> 00:14:59.370
the genetic marker
for that disease,

00:14:59.370 --> 00:15:01.220
if they are a candidate for it?

00:15:01.220 --> 00:15:04.750
And this opened up a
whole world of confusion

00:15:04.750 --> 00:15:08.510
about this, where a key
feature of these debates

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:11.720
was the fact that you
haven't gotten the gene.

00:15:11.720 --> 00:15:14.850
You've just gotten the
candidate stretch of DNA,

00:15:14.850 --> 00:15:18.520
and there remains a very
small statistical chance

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:20.970
that you've got the wrong one.

00:15:20.970 --> 00:15:23.650
For a bunch of reasons,
there is that possibility.

00:15:23.650 --> 00:15:26.520
So do you let
somebody take a test?

00:15:26.520 --> 00:15:29.360
Can people tell the difference
between a yes and no

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:31.240
and a statistical probability?

00:15:31.240 --> 00:15:34.310
What do you do if it's a disease
where the person has just spent

00:15:34.310 --> 00:15:36.690
their last 10 years
watching their parents

00:15:36.690 --> 00:15:39.430
slowly die from it, and
there's no cure for it,

00:15:39.430 --> 00:15:40.810
and it's absolutely horrible?

00:15:40.810 --> 00:15:43.516
Do you give them a test that
is-- if the bad outcome is

00:15:43.516 --> 00:15:45.390
going to throw them off
the top of a building

00:15:45.390 --> 00:15:46.740
with a high likelihood?

00:15:46.740 --> 00:15:49.970
Enormously complex
bioethics issue.

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:53.280
The third challenge, though,
was to step up the science

00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:55.550
from just having
the stretch of DNA

00:15:55.550 --> 00:15:59.270
with a bunch of genes in there
to actually find the gene.

00:15:59.270 --> 00:16:02.400
And in the years since, the
molecular biology has gotten

00:16:02.400 --> 00:16:07.310
much, much better at moving
past finding a genetic marker,

00:16:07.310 --> 00:16:11.040
we are 99.9% certain that
the gene that's relevant

00:16:11.040 --> 00:16:14.450
is somewhere in this stretch,
to finding the actual gene

00:16:14.450 --> 00:16:16.300
and then being
able to see what's

00:16:16.300 --> 00:16:19.060
the difference in it
between them and them.

00:16:19.060 --> 00:16:22.080
What's the difference,
down to base pairs?

00:16:22.080 --> 00:16:23.660
Where is the mutation?

00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:25.430
Where's the difference
coming from?

00:16:25.430 --> 00:16:28.540
That's the world of
sequencing genomes now.

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:30.570
That's where the field is at.

00:16:30.570 --> 00:16:34.480
So that has been enormously
powerful in terms

00:16:34.480 --> 00:16:38.550
of potentially finding
one single gene.

00:16:38.550 --> 00:16:41.840
But everything that came through
in the molecular lectures

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:44.260
last week should be
pointing out there's

00:16:44.260 --> 00:16:46.150
not a whole lot
going on in there

00:16:46.150 --> 00:16:49.770
that revolves around one
single gene at a time.

00:16:49.770 --> 00:16:52.570
So hold on to really
horrible diseases.

00:16:52.570 --> 00:16:55.660
Yeah, one gene, single
mutation, but most of what

00:16:55.660 --> 00:16:58.070
goes wrong, if you want
to start understanding

00:16:58.070 --> 00:17:03.120
the genetics of psychiatric
disorders, of diabetes,

00:17:03.120 --> 00:17:07.099
of early-- of late-onset
dementias, things of that sort,

00:17:07.099 --> 00:17:09.390
it's not going to
be just one gene.

00:17:09.390 --> 00:17:11.710
So the next huge
advance in the field

00:17:11.710 --> 00:17:16.109
was being able to do searches
like these for multiple genes.

00:17:16.109 --> 00:17:18.800
One thing that has been
used is a technique called

00:17:18.800 --> 00:17:21.369
microarrays, gene microarrays.

00:17:21.369 --> 00:17:24.150
And they were basically
invented here on campus by a guy

00:17:24.150 --> 00:17:27.720
over in the med school named
Pat Brown, who is already

00:17:27.720 --> 00:17:29.880
very famous for
having done this and I

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:32.590
suspect has all sorts of
interesting awards coming

00:17:32.590 --> 00:17:33.960
for him down the line.

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:37.930
This spectacular technique-- you
take what is now called a gene

00:17:37.930 --> 00:17:41.320
chip, and through techniques
that are absolutely boggling

00:17:41.320 --> 00:17:45.050
and make me feel queasy,
what you somehow manage to do

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:48.580
is you get all the
copies of RNA that

00:17:48.580 --> 00:17:52.790
could be made in a cell
from this individual.

00:17:52.790 --> 00:17:54.830
If you are completely
new to this

00:17:54.830 --> 00:17:56.650
and you've managed
to get in this far

00:17:56.650 --> 00:17:59.350
without having to think
about what RNA is, ignore it.

00:17:59.350 --> 00:18:01.396
This is just sort of a
subtle detail for people

00:18:01.396 --> 00:18:02.520
who are interested in this.

00:18:02.520 --> 00:18:05.910
What you do is you get
a copy of each type

00:18:05.910 --> 00:18:08.170
of RNA made in a cell.

00:18:08.170 --> 00:18:12.420
You force the cell basically
to transcribe all of the genes

00:18:12.420 --> 00:18:13.160
it has.

00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:15.100
And then you get
this little chip,

00:18:15.100 --> 00:18:18.730
and you basically glue the
end of each one of these RNAs

00:18:18.730 --> 00:18:21.100
to it, and you will
have a chip with 20,000

00:18:21.100 --> 00:18:22.520
of these little things.

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:25.030
And then you use
probes which will

00:18:25.030 --> 00:18:30.160
allow you to see which versions
of 20,000 of those genes

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:33.290
are different in this
individual from that individual.

00:18:33.290 --> 00:18:36.950
Total boggling, has
forced an entire new world

00:18:36.950 --> 00:18:40.780
of trying to analyze data,
this new field of informatics

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:43.020
because you're not looking
at one gene at a time.

00:18:43.020 --> 00:18:47.000
You're looking at patterns,
and that becomes a lot harder.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.060
That becomes
incredibly important

00:18:49.060 --> 00:18:53.240
because, again, it's all sorts
of the interesting stuff where

00:18:53.240 --> 00:18:54.490
it's not going to be one gene.

00:18:54.490 --> 00:18:55.330
It's a dozen.

00:18:55.330 --> 00:18:56.600
It's 100.

00:18:56.600 --> 00:18:59.490
So that has been one
challenging approach.

00:18:59.490 --> 00:19:03.730
Another is a technique called
QTLs, quantitative trait

00:19:03.730 --> 00:19:04.440
lowside.

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:06.660
What that basically
is built around--

00:19:06.660 --> 00:19:09.990
that if you have subtle enough
of tests, you could figure out

00:19:09.990 --> 00:19:14.550
this is a complex trait that
is modulated by two genes,

00:19:14.550 --> 00:19:17.510
or by three, or by 17.

00:19:17.510 --> 00:19:19.550
You can see all of this
going in the direction

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:22.170
from techniques that
would let you know

00:19:22.170 --> 00:19:25.030
you're kind of in the
neighborhood of a gene,

00:19:25.030 --> 00:19:28.180
to actually identifying a gene
that differs between the two

00:19:28.180 --> 00:19:31.710
populations, to the much
more useful realistic world

00:19:31.710 --> 00:19:36.390
of whole bunches of genes,
networks going on at a time.

00:19:36.390 --> 00:19:38.330
So using these
approaches, people

00:19:38.330 --> 00:19:40.190
have made lots of progress.

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:41.970
The most recent
version of that--

00:19:41.970 --> 00:19:44.260
I mentioned the other
day there, one type

00:19:44.260 --> 00:19:47.800
of mutation, a macro
mutation, is this business

00:19:47.800 --> 00:19:52.770
about variants of major
stretches of DNA copy length

00:19:52.770 --> 00:19:54.720
variance, where a
whole stretch of DNA

00:19:54.720 --> 00:19:58.250
is duplicated twice or
eleventy different times.

00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:01.250
Can you identify traits
that are occurring

00:20:01.250 --> 00:20:04.180
because of differences
in the number of copies?

00:20:04.180 --> 00:20:06.830
Yet another version
of dealing with

00:20:06.830 --> 00:20:11.560
this whole hierarchical,
multi-level business about gene

00:20:11.560 --> 00:20:12.650
regulation.

00:20:12.650 --> 00:20:15.670
OK, take home message
from this is 20,

00:20:15.670 --> 00:20:17.640
30 years ago when
all of this started,

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:21.830
you can start with a trait, and
through increasingly fancier

00:20:21.830 --> 00:20:24.960
techniques, you could find
the neighborhood of where

00:20:24.960 --> 00:20:29.060
the gene is that the
different versions of the gene

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:31.990
correspond to the different
versions of the trait-- moving

00:20:31.990 --> 00:20:35.450
from patterns of that to the
neighborhood of the genes

00:20:35.450 --> 00:20:38.310
to the actual gene to
whole bunches of genes

00:20:38.310 --> 00:20:42.060
to macro differences
there, that's one approach.

00:20:42.060 --> 00:20:43.830
The other approach
of the field has

00:20:43.830 --> 00:20:45.670
been starting the other way.

00:20:45.670 --> 00:20:47.220
You've got a gene.

00:20:47.220 --> 00:20:49.920
You've got a gene, and
thanks to researching it

00:20:49.920 --> 00:20:53.350
in flies, and worms, and
rats, and all of that,

00:20:53.350 --> 00:20:55.880
you kind of have a sense
of what the gene does,

00:20:55.880 --> 00:20:59.380
and you have a reasonable
guess of what sort of traits

00:20:59.380 --> 00:21:01.850
might be relevant in
a human, and now you

00:21:01.850 --> 00:21:03.390
run it the other way.

00:21:03.390 --> 00:21:06.100
You have two different
versions of the gene,

00:21:06.100 --> 00:21:09.180
and you look for
differences in behavior,

00:21:09.180 --> 00:21:11.350
or differences in
protein function,

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:13.630
or differences in the
size of the protein.

00:21:13.630 --> 00:21:15.540
You start with the
genetic knowledge.

00:21:15.540 --> 00:21:18.830
And for our purposes, where
people are mostly looking

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:21.380
is at behavioral end points.

00:21:21.380 --> 00:21:23.050
So what do you see with that?

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:26.570
Lots of findings in recent
years, and my feeling

00:21:26.570 --> 00:21:28.970
is this is one of the more
interesting ways of doing

00:21:28.970 --> 00:21:30.790
this behavior
genetics-- starting

00:21:30.790 --> 00:21:32.820
with basic research
with animals.

00:21:32.820 --> 00:21:34.850
You've got some sense
of what the gene does.

00:21:34.850 --> 00:21:36.390
How about it in people?

00:21:36.390 --> 00:21:38.530
Because there is variability.

00:21:38.530 --> 00:21:42.700
First example, and this has to
do with a really interesting

00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:45.570
hormone that we will hear
plenty about down the line,

00:21:45.570 --> 00:21:47.860
a hormone called vasopressin.

00:21:47.860 --> 00:21:52.660
And vasopressin in rodents
I think I already discussed.

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:57.110
Vasopressin in rodents has
a receptor, the vasopressin

00:21:57.110 --> 00:21:57.730
receptor.

00:21:57.730 --> 00:22:00.810
And what we talked about
the other week is depending

00:22:00.810 --> 00:22:03.200
on which version
of this you have,

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:06.020
if you happen to
be a vole male, it

00:22:06.020 --> 00:22:07.600
will determine
whether or not you

00:22:07.600 --> 00:22:10.020
were monogamous or polygamous.

00:22:10.020 --> 00:22:11.180
That's interesting.

00:22:11.180 --> 00:22:14.090
What was also interesting
was that difference-- the two

00:22:14.090 --> 00:22:18.240
variants were not in the gene
itself but in the promoter,

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:22.140
and that winds up meaning that
the promoter caused in one

00:22:22.140 --> 00:22:27.080
strain the gene to be expressed
in different parts of the brain

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:28.900
than in the other version of it.

00:22:28.900 --> 00:22:32.570
OK, so what we saw there was all
sorts of hints from the animal

00:22:32.570 --> 00:22:37.320
world that vasopressin has stuff
to do with social affiliation,

00:22:37.320 --> 00:22:38.600
things of that sort.

00:22:38.600 --> 00:22:40.460
So what do you now do
if you want to apply

00:22:40.460 --> 00:22:42.080
this knowledge to humans?

00:22:42.080 --> 00:22:45.420
The first thing you
need to ask is, well,

00:22:45.420 --> 00:22:47.570
do we know where the
gene is in humans?

00:22:47.570 --> 00:22:50.370
And with modern sequencing
in the human genome,

00:22:50.370 --> 00:22:53.640
you've got it, so you know where
the gene is for the vasopressin

00:22:53.640 --> 00:22:54.460
receptor.

00:22:54.460 --> 00:22:56.040
And the next thing
you have to ask

00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:59.300
is, does it come in
two different flavors?

00:22:59.300 --> 00:23:01.170
Does it come in two
different flavors,

00:23:01.170 --> 00:23:03.690
and do they differ
in the same way

00:23:03.690 --> 00:23:06.930
as the ones people have
studied endlessly in rodents?

00:23:06.930 --> 00:23:07.720
Yay.

00:23:07.720 --> 00:23:11.190
Yes, indeed, the receptor
gene is exactly the same

00:23:11.190 --> 00:23:13.350
in everyone, but there's
two different versions

00:23:13.350 --> 00:23:16.520
of the promoter--
the same exact story.

00:23:16.520 --> 00:23:17.810
So that's great.

00:23:17.810 --> 00:23:20.230
If you've gotten
that far, now you

00:23:20.230 --> 00:23:22.970
start looking for what
the differences are

00:23:22.970 --> 00:23:27.340
between people who have one
variant versus the other.

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:28.840
And you've got to
do your homework.

00:23:28.840 --> 00:23:33.390
You got to match them for
age, and gender, and number

00:23:33.390 --> 00:23:35.520
of cavities, and all
sorts of stuff like that.

00:23:35.520 --> 00:23:37.150
And when you've got
that under control,

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:39.250
you go looking for behaviors.

00:23:39.250 --> 00:23:40.930
What's the limit of this?

00:23:40.930 --> 00:23:43.330
By definition, you're
only looking where

00:23:43.330 --> 00:23:44.830
the light is shining already.

00:23:44.830 --> 00:23:46.480
You're only looking
where you already

00:23:46.480 --> 00:23:49.380
have a sense that maybe
you should be looking,

00:23:49.380 --> 00:23:51.440
unless you're totally
crazy-obsessive

00:23:51.440 --> 00:23:54.430
and want to try to measure
everything possible in people

00:23:54.430 --> 00:23:55.800
and look for a difference.

00:23:55.800 --> 00:23:59.004
In most of these studies, you
kind of know where to look.

00:23:59.004 --> 00:24:00.670
That immediately means
there's all sorts

00:24:00.670 --> 00:24:02.280
of areas you're not looking.

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:04.200
Nonetheless, with
this approach, people

00:24:04.200 --> 00:24:08.080
have gone looking in humans
at these different variants

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:10.690
on the vasopressin
receptor gene,

00:24:10.690 --> 00:24:13.910
and you find some really
interesting differences.

00:24:13.910 --> 00:24:17.220
One was a paper published
a couple years ago

00:24:17.220 --> 00:24:19.330
in a very prestigious
journal, which

00:24:19.330 --> 00:24:22.050
got picked up in the papers
all over the universe,

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:25.690
showing if you have the
version of the promoter

00:24:25.690 --> 00:24:30.340
that you find in monogamous
male voles, you as a human male

00:24:30.340 --> 00:24:34.470
are likely to have more stable
relationships than if you

00:24:34.470 --> 00:24:36.420
have the other version of it.

00:24:36.420 --> 00:24:37.690
Whoa.

00:24:37.690 --> 00:24:39.700
That's pretty bizarre.

00:24:39.700 --> 00:24:41.050
That's pretty cool.

00:24:41.050 --> 00:24:43.300
Next thing, a study
that just came out

00:24:43.300 --> 00:24:46.050
in that same prestigious
journal a couple of weeks ago,

00:24:46.050 --> 00:24:47.660
and this is one
we're showing, which,

00:24:47.660 --> 00:24:50.920
depending on which version
you have, how good are you

00:24:50.920 --> 00:24:54.030
reading facial expressions
in other people?

00:24:54.030 --> 00:24:56.780
Subtle differences in
facial expressions--

00:24:56.780 --> 00:25:00.010
then, there's a whole
other world of approaching,

00:25:00.010 --> 00:25:04.590
evidence emerging that in
families where autism runs

00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:08.820
majorly through the families,
people are seeing mutations

00:25:08.820 --> 00:25:13.010
in genes related to vasopressin
and the vasopressin receptor.

00:25:13.010 --> 00:25:15.480
So this is one
really cool example

00:25:15.480 --> 00:25:17.760
of starting with that
approach, and this

00:25:17.760 --> 00:25:20.420
is a gene whose
variants have something

00:25:20.420 --> 00:25:23.280
to do with some pretty
meaningful realms

00:25:23.280 --> 00:25:27.380
of human social connectiveness,
variability stuff.

00:25:27.380 --> 00:25:29.150
Totally interesting.

00:25:29.150 --> 00:25:34.340
Another example-- this is
a gene coding for a protein

00:25:34.340 --> 00:25:39.274
called BDNF, brain-derived
neurotrophic factor.

00:25:39.274 --> 00:25:40.190
Doesn't really matter.

00:25:40.190 --> 00:25:44.030
The main point of BDNF
is it prompts neurons

00:25:44.030 --> 00:25:47.320
into growing new processes.

00:25:47.320 --> 00:25:49.950
And it turns out, BDNF does
something that ultimately

00:25:49.950 --> 00:25:51.640
is kind of a drag for you.

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:53.836
In one part of the
brain, the amygdala,

00:25:53.836 --> 00:25:55.960
which-- I think I've already
mentioned the amygdala

00:25:55.960 --> 00:26:00.280
has a lot to do with fear and
anxiety and that sort of thing,

00:26:00.280 --> 00:26:01.820
and we will come back to that.

00:26:01.820 --> 00:26:02.630
Don't panic.

00:26:02.630 --> 00:26:08.390
But the main thing is BDNF plays
a role in causing individuals--

00:26:08.390 --> 00:26:12.580
individual rats-- when they
are highly stressed to make

00:26:12.580 --> 00:26:16.980
the neurons in the amygdala grow
new connections, new processes.

00:26:16.980 --> 00:26:18.100
What are you doing?

00:26:18.100 --> 00:26:20.420
You are training that
rat to be anxious.

00:26:20.420 --> 00:26:22.790
You are training that rat
to be hyper-responsive

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:24.130
to scary things.

00:26:24.130 --> 00:26:27.170
BDNF appears to play this role.

00:26:27.170 --> 00:26:30.030
So now, the next step in
this sequence-- and you'll

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:33.060
begin to see it's the same
pattern over and over-- people

00:26:33.060 --> 00:26:37.430
then found, ah, there's a couple
of different flavors of BDNF.

00:26:37.430 --> 00:26:40.320
There are a couple of
different genetic variants.

00:26:40.320 --> 00:26:41.860
There's a couple
of different ways

00:26:41.860 --> 00:26:45.750
in which BDNF pops up in
rats or mice or whatever,

00:26:45.750 --> 00:26:50.020
differing by a base pair
here, an amino acid there,

00:26:50.020 --> 00:26:53.330
where you then do your
scutwork and show, OK,

00:26:53.330 --> 00:26:59.200
this BDNF works faster than that
version of it or it works less

00:26:59.200 --> 00:27:01.820
but it lasts longer,
or who knows what.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:03.710
You find a functional
difference.

00:27:03.710 --> 00:27:05.620
There's a genetic difference.

00:27:05.620 --> 00:27:07.274
There's two different
versions of it,

00:27:07.274 --> 00:27:08.690
and it actually
makes a difference

00:27:08.690 --> 00:27:10.280
for how the protein functions.

00:27:10.280 --> 00:27:12.450
And this has all been
studied in animals,

00:27:12.450 --> 00:27:16.360
and now you understand what it's
doing in the amygdala of a rat,

00:27:16.360 --> 00:27:17.910
depending on which
version you have.

00:27:17.910 --> 00:27:20.920
And then the exact
same strategy--

00:27:20.920 --> 00:27:24.720
go look at the BDNF gene
in humans and ask, well,

00:27:24.720 --> 00:27:26.930
do you see the same difference?

00:27:26.930 --> 00:27:29.620
Are the same two
flavors in humans

00:27:29.620 --> 00:27:30.900
popping up as in rodents?

00:27:30.900 --> 00:27:31.820
Yes, indeed.

00:27:31.820 --> 00:27:34.150
And then, the exact
same approach again,

00:27:34.150 --> 00:27:37.240
looking for differences, and
you know where to start looking.

00:27:37.240 --> 00:27:39.340
What has that
literature been showing?

00:27:39.340 --> 00:27:42.360
The type of BDNF
variant that you

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:45.890
have in the exact same way
that it maps in rodents maps

00:27:45.890 --> 00:27:49.550
onto your likelihood
of an anxiety disorder,

00:27:49.550 --> 00:27:52.870
the levels of stress
hormones in your bloodstream,

00:27:52.870 --> 00:27:56.980
the levels of metabolic
activity in your amygdala,

00:27:56.980 --> 00:27:59.460
the same exact sort of finding.

00:27:59.460 --> 00:28:02.560
Next, a whole other
world, which we will learn

00:28:02.560 --> 00:28:04.090
much more about down the line.

00:28:04.090 --> 00:28:06.390
This is obviously a quick
survey of a whole bunch

00:28:06.390 --> 00:28:07.290
of different areas.

00:28:07.290 --> 00:28:09.820
All of these we will
come back to big time

00:28:09.820 --> 00:28:11.010
later on in the course.

00:28:11.010 --> 00:28:13.550
Next area, this
neurotransmitter,

00:28:13.550 --> 00:28:17.220
dopamine-- you will learn
amazing amounts about dopamine.

00:28:17.220 --> 00:28:19.250
Dopamine, which
works through a-- you

00:28:19.250 --> 00:28:22.190
guessed it-- dopamine
receptor-- and in fact, there

00:28:22.190 --> 00:28:25.370
is a gazillion different
types of dopamine receptors.

00:28:25.370 --> 00:28:28.930
And dopamine
receptor number four,

00:28:28.930 --> 00:28:32.040
D4, the dopamine
receptor four gene

00:28:32.040 --> 00:28:35.180
has something to do with a whole
bunch of interesting traits

00:28:35.180 --> 00:28:36.380
in rodents.

00:28:36.380 --> 00:28:40.250
And it comes with variability
in the rodent versions,

00:28:40.250 --> 00:28:43.240
different flavors, and
humans have variability

00:28:43.240 --> 00:28:44.650
along similar lines.

00:28:44.650 --> 00:28:47.520
And dopamine-- what is
dopamine involved in?

00:28:47.520 --> 00:28:54.030
Pleasure, and anticipation,
and reward-seeking behavior.

00:28:54.030 --> 00:28:57.190
What two different versions
of the dopamine type

00:28:57.190 --> 00:29:02.210
four, the D4 receptor gene,
begin to map onto in humans?

00:29:02.210 --> 00:29:07.960
Levels of risk-taking behavior,
levels of sensation seeking,

00:29:07.960 --> 00:29:11.390
levels of novelty craving.

00:29:11.390 --> 00:29:13.330
That's interesting.

00:29:13.330 --> 00:29:18.200
Another example, a gene
called NPY-- a protein,

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:22.330
a neurotransmitter called
neuropeptide Y. Do not get

00:29:22.330 --> 00:29:23.740
overwhelmed by all of these.

00:29:23.740 --> 00:29:26.050
It's just the same
pattern over and over.

00:29:26.050 --> 00:29:30.590
NPY, same deal again-- and
two different human variants

00:29:30.590 --> 00:29:33.760
have something to do with
differences in levels,

00:29:33.760 --> 00:29:38.760
again, of anxiety, of metabolic
rates in the amygdala,

00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:40.500
all of that.

00:29:40.500 --> 00:29:42.150
And in this case,
the NPY difference

00:29:42.150 --> 00:29:43.910
is quite interesting
because it's

00:29:43.910 --> 00:29:45.810
one of those where
the difference is not

00:29:45.810 --> 00:29:47.950
in the gene structure sequence.

00:29:47.950 --> 00:29:50.530
It's once again a
difference in the promoter.

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:53.270
OK, so what have we
have in all of these?

00:29:53.270 --> 00:29:55.470
This is a really
powerful approach.

00:29:55.470 --> 00:29:57.590
The first version
that we heard, you've

00:29:57.590 --> 00:29:59.190
got a behavioral difference.

00:29:59.190 --> 00:30:01.880
You've got a
phenotypic difference.

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:05.040
You've got a difference in
how two proteins function,

00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:06.120
or their size.

00:30:06.120 --> 00:30:09.520
Go looking for what's the
genetic difference between

00:30:09.520 --> 00:30:11.910
those who have this trait
and those who don't.

00:30:11.910 --> 00:30:14.350
This version, reverse
engineering it,

00:30:14.350 --> 00:30:18.310
you start off with a gene that
comes in different flavors.

00:30:18.310 --> 00:30:20.850
You got a sense of what it
does from animal studies.

00:30:20.850 --> 00:30:23.810
Do you have the same
variation in humans,

00:30:23.810 --> 00:30:25.770
and does it map onto behavior?

00:30:25.770 --> 00:30:27.720
So all of these are amazing.

00:30:27.720 --> 00:30:29.980
All of these, it
has to be emphasized

00:30:29.980 --> 00:30:32.290
in a way that will come
back to haunt us also

00:30:32.290 --> 00:30:37.100
big time-- all of these
explain tiny percentages

00:30:37.100 --> 00:30:40.040
of the variability in the data.

00:30:40.040 --> 00:30:42.270
There is nothing
remotely resembling

00:30:42.270 --> 00:30:45.220
a world in which
if you have flavor

00:30:45.220 --> 00:30:48.790
vanilla of the D4 receptor
versus if you have flavor

00:30:48.790 --> 00:30:50.970
chocolate-- if you
have flavor vanilla,

00:30:50.970 --> 00:30:54.560
you are going to be hand gliding
when you are in preschool.

00:30:54.560 --> 00:30:56.890
You're going to be
totally sensation seeking.

00:30:56.890 --> 00:30:58.399
And if you have
the other version,

00:30:58.399 --> 00:31:00.440
you're going to spend your
entire life collecting

00:31:00.440 --> 00:31:02.510
stamps or who knows what.

00:31:02.510 --> 00:31:04.270
It's not that deterministic.

00:31:04.270 --> 00:31:06.930
No surprise with
this gene stuff.

00:31:06.930 --> 00:31:10.560
No single gene is going to
be particularly deterministic

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:14.300
once you get outside the
world of phenylketonuria

00:31:14.300 --> 00:31:16.160
and cystic fibrosis and such.

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:19.900
They contribute some
explanatory power.

00:31:19.900 --> 00:31:24.620
So on one hand, amazingly cool,
seeing these genetic links

00:31:24.620 --> 00:31:26.850
to aspects of human behavior.

00:31:26.850 --> 00:31:29.540
On the other hand, they're
not very big effects,

00:31:29.540 --> 00:31:31.190
and this is something
we will come back

00:31:31.190 --> 00:31:33.020
to endlessly down the line.

00:31:33.020 --> 00:31:38.030
OK, so this is how the field has
gone about more recently trying

00:31:38.030 --> 00:31:43.320
to find links between variation
in genes or their promoters

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:47.740
and variations in aspect of
behavior, running it both ways.

00:31:47.740 --> 00:31:50.020
And what all of
this is looking at,

00:31:50.020 --> 00:31:51.880
what is intrinsic
in everything we've

00:31:51.880 --> 00:31:53.900
been talking about with
this behavior genetics,

00:31:53.900 --> 00:31:56.960
is oh, my God, the
cliche finally emerges.

00:31:56.960 --> 00:32:00.690
Nature and nurture, and
gene and environment,

00:32:00.690 --> 00:32:02.630
and gene/environment
interactions--

00:32:02.630 --> 00:32:05.500
what is becoming increasingly
clear in the field

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:09.170
is there's a third
leg to all of this.

00:32:09.170 --> 00:32:12.550
There's a third leg that
could be extremely powerful

00:32:12.550 --> 00:32:16.000
and is going to be the basis
for the chaos and complexity

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:19.280
lectures down the
line, which is chance,

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:22.360
the role of random
events, the role

00:32:22.360 --> 00:32:27.300
of chance in being a form that
transcends what we would call

00:32:27.300 --> 00:32:30.300
environment and is
certainly not genetics,

00:32:30.300 --> 00:32:33.240
a whole different world
where that contributes.

00:32:33.240 --> 00:32:37.290
OK, where will we see chance
playing out an important role

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:38.400
in all of this?

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:43.270
Brownian motion-- for those who
don't have a techie background,

00:32:43.270 --> 00:32:45.490
I will describe it in the
way that I understand it,

00:32:45.490 --> 00:32:47.300
which is flailing desperately.

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:51.310
Brownian motion has to do
with the fact that molecules

00:32:51.310 --> 00:32:56.380
oscillate and use an intrinsic
movement, oscillation,

00:32:56.380 --> 00:32:57.600
of molecules.

00:32:57.600 --> 00:32:59.890
You take a whatever
full of water

00:32:59.890 --> 00:33:02.830
filled with all sorts of
things-- molecules, whatever--

00:33:02.830 --> 00:33:04.550
and they're all
going to be vibrating

00:33:04.550 --> 00:33:07.680
to a certain extent because
of this Brownian motion.

00:33:07.680 --> 00:33:11.180
I suspect that was the most
amazingly incorrect description

00:33:11.180 --> 00:33:13.830
of what Brownian motion
is, but that's the point.

00:33:13.830 --> 00:33:17.480
That's the main point, simply
that there is this oscillation,

00:33:17.480 --> 00:33:19.820
which is completely random.

00:33:19.820 --> 00:33:22.310
It is just an intrinsic
feature of how

00:33:22.310 --> 00:33:26.430
the world of physics and Albert
Einstein's mustache works.

00:33:26.430 --> 00:33:29.750
And so you've got this
Brownian motion stuff going on.

00:33:29.750 --> 00:33:33.190
So where might that play
out in terms of chance?

00:33:33.190 --> 00:33:39.300
So we got here a cell with our
four powerhouses of the cell

00:33:39.300 --> 00:33:39.860
here.

00:33:39.860 --> 00:33:42.890
And on the right-- let's assume
this is a genetically identical

00:33:42.890 --> 00:33:45.810
cell, and I just got tired
of drawing it completely--

00:33:45.810 --> 00:33:47.690
but the same four mitochondria.

00:33:47.690 --> 00:33:51.050
And what we see here
first off is genetically,

00:33:51.050 --> 00:33:53.070
these mitochondria differ.

00:33:53.070 --> 00:33:54.380
One of them has a blue spot.

00:33:54.380 --> 00:33:55.630
One of them has a red sweater.

00:33:55.630 --> 00:33:57.160
Wait a second.

00:33:57.160 --> 00:33:59.740
Every single cell in
your body was built out

00:33:59.740 --> 00:34:02.960
of the same genome when
you started off life.

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:03.760
Ah-ha.

00:34:03.760 --> 00:34:05.770
Back to that thing
the other day.

00:34:05.770 --> 00:34:08.870
Mitochondria have their own DNA.

00:34:08.870 --> 00:34:11.480
Mitochondria are going
about their own business

00:34:11.480 --> 00:34:14.710
of dividing in the
cell, of replicating

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:18.800
their-- replicating themselves
now and then with a mutation.

00:34:18.800 --> 00:34:23.550
Within any given cell, the
mitochondrial sequence of DNA

00:34:23.550 --> 00:34:26.179
is going to differ from
one mitochondria to another

00:34:26.179 --> 00:34:28.949
because they've been
separate organisms that

00:34:28.949 --> 00:34:32.400
are inside a cell going
about their own evolution,

00:34:32.400 --> 00:34:34.770
their own mutations,
their own whatever.

00:34:34.770 --> 00:34:36.909
What you then
have-- what would be

00:34:36.909 --> 00:34:41.280
called a mosaic of
different genetic profiles

00:34:41.280 --> 00:34:44.070
of the mitochondria
within a cell.

00:34:44.070 --> 00:34:46.929
So that in and of itself
is pretty interesting

00:34:46.929 --> 00:34:49.040
because this is a
whole other world.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:52.909
This is not the DNA
back in the nucleus,

00:34:52.909 --> 00:34:55.630
and this is not
variability introduced

00:34:55.630 --> 00:34:59.580
by jumping genes or
accessibility of transcription

00:34:59.580 --> 00:35:01.120
factors to genes, all that.

00:35:01.120 --> 00:35:03.730
This is-- meanwhile,
outside the nucleus,

00:35:03.730 --> 00:35:07.070
there's this whole weirdo world
of these mitochondria that

00:35:07.070 --> 00:35:08.780
are functioning
all on their own,

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:11.830
so the different
mitochondria in the same cell

00:35:11.830 --> 00:35:14.720
will have different
genetic makeups.

00:35:14.720 --> 00:35:15.620
So great.

00:35:15.620 --> 00:35:17.930
So these two cells are
absolutely identical.

00:35:17.930 --> 00:35:20.810
Each of them have four
mitochondria, and each of them

00:35:20.810 --> 00:35:22.650
have two red kinds,
one blue kind,

00:35:22.650 --> 00:35:24.250
and one that gets nothing.

00:35:24.250 --> 00:35:28.700
So now that cell is going to
go about splitting in two.

00:35:28.700 --> 00:35:33.550
And what happens is it splits.

00:35:33.550 --> 00:35:37.260
And in the process of splitting,
what the fluid, the cytosol,

00:35:37.260 --> 00:35:40.250
the stuff inside where all
the molecules-- including

00:35:40.250 --> 00:35:43.140
the mitochondria in the
other organelles-- are found.

00:35:43.140 --> 00:35:45.630
And it splits,
and there winds up

00:35:45.630 --> 00:35:47.180
being a very simple question.

00:35:47.180 --> 00:35:51.890
Which mitochondria wind
up in which daughter cell?

00:35:51.890 --> 00:35:56.460
And what we've got here is in
this case, a split like that.

00:35:56.460 --> 00:35:58.580
In this case, a split like that.

00:35:58.580 --> 00:35:59.900
Oh my god, why did that happen?

00:35:59.900 --> 00:36:02.220
Is that because there is
a gene in this one that

00:36:02.220 --> 00:36:06.460
says when you form a new pair
of cells, have blue and blank

00:36:06.460 --> 00:36:08.110
in one and two
reds in the other?

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:11.900
And this one is a completely
different instruction manual

00:36:11.900 --> 00:36:13.270
for how you split cells.

00:36:13.270 --> 00:36:17.360
No, simple randomness of
where the mitochondria were

00:36:17.360 --> 00:36:19.390
in the cell when they split.

00:36:19.390 --> 00:36:22.110
A totally random event.

00:36:22.110 --> 00:36:24.830
So what you see here
is you start off

00:36:24.830 --> 00:36:28.320
with two cells that are
genetically identical.

00:36:28.320 --> 00:36:31.270
And within one round
of cell splitting,

00:36:31.270 --> 00:36:33.710
these genetically
identical individuals

00:36:33.710 --> 00:36:36.080
are already
genetically different.

00:36:36.080 --> 00:36:37.040
How come?

00:36:37.040 --> 00:36:39.010
Because of instructions
or a blueprint?

00:36:39.010 --> 00:36:39.560
No.

00:36:39.560 --> 00:36:42.950
Simply because
molecules, organelles,

00:36:42.950 --> 00:36:45.340
things like mitochondria
just oscillating around.

00:36:45.340 --> 00:36:48.700
And along comes a split, and
who is stuck on which side

00:36:48.700 --> 00:36:49.690
of the divide.

00:36:49.690 --> 00:36:52.600
So you've got
variability that way.

00:36:52.600 --> 00:36:56.100
Intrinsic in that is another
type of variability, which

00:36:56.100 --> 00:36:57.490
the second I
mention it, you will

00:36:57.490 --> 00:36:59.660
be able to run
with effortlessly,

00:36:59.660 --> 00:37:02.740
which is floating
around in here also

00:37:02.740 --> 00:37:07.670
will be transcription
factors, and splicing enzymes,

00:37:07.670 --> 00:37:09.320
and other enzymes.

00:37:09.320 --> 00:37:11.860
And along comes the split.

00:37:11.860 --> 00:37:13.910
And there is not
the remotest chance

00:37:13.910 --> 00:37:17.320
that half of every single
type of transcription factor

00:37:17.320 --> 00:37:20.110
is going to go each way, and
half of every type of splicing

00:37:20.110 --> 00:37:21.690
enzyme, et cetera.

00:37:21.690 --> 00:37:24.060
It's going to be who's
oscillating where

00:37:24.060 --> 00:37:26.110
and where the cells splits.

00:37:26.110 --> 00:37:30.090
So you wind up not only
with different outcomes

00:37:30.090 --> 00:37:32.317
in terms of mitochondria
and their genetic makeup,

00:37:32.317 --> 00:37:34.150
you're going to have
different distributions

00:37:34.150 --> 00:37:36.330
of different types of
transcription factors.

00:37:36.330 --> 00:37:40.790
All due to this random
oscillatory stuff.

00:37:40.790 --> 00:37:44.150
So that's one big component
where chance plays a role.

00:37:44.150 --> 00:37:46.310
And what the chaos
complexity lectures

00:37:46.310 --> 00:37:48.120
are going to be
very heavily about

00:37:48.120 --> 00:37:50.530
is just how important
stuff like this

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:55.440
is, how important it is in
explaining what goes on,

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:58.610
how important it is in
explaining why, no matter

00:37:58.610 --> 00:38:01.780
how much you know about what
every single molecule is having

00:38:01.780 --> 00:38:03.850
for lunch next
Tuesday, there's still

00:38:03.850 --> 00:38:07.100
going to be a huge degree
of unpredictability.

00:38:07.100 --> 00:38:08.520
All of that is to come.

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:11.770
This is just beginning to
establish the idea yes, nature,

00:38:11.770 --> 00:38:13.130
nurture, nature, nurture.

00:38:13.130 --> 00:38:16.960
Chance also is the third leg
in there playing a large role.

00:38:16.960 --> 00:38:20.020
Whether chance is
what's going on when

00:38:20.020 --> 00:38:23.270
you get a transposable event--
you remember at the point

00:38:23.270 --> 00:38:26.220
that neural stem cells
are beginning to divide

00:38:26.220 --> 00:38:27.190
into neurons.

00:38:27.190 --> 00:38:30.270
That's when they juggle around
their transposable genes

00:38:30.270 --> 00:38:31.430
most dramatically.

00:38:31.430 --> 00:38:34.840
Whether that is a completely
random event as to where

00:38:34.840 --> 00:38:37.710
the copies land when
they come back to Earth,

00:38:37.710 --> 00:38:39.400
I'm not sure if people know.

00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:42.580
But I suspect there's an
element of chance in there also.

00:38:42.580 --> 00:38:45.560
So this is introducing
that notion in there.

00:38:45.560 --> 00:38:46.230
So great.

00:38:46.230 --> 00:38:48.460
So now you've got
all these caviats,

00:38:48.460 --> 00:38:51.020
which is environment
is subtle and coming

00:38:51.020 --> 00:38:53.350
all over the place,
and early experience,

00:38:53.350 --> 00:38:57.100
and epigenetic changes, and all
the different ways you could

00:38:57.100 --> 00:38:59.160
find genes linked to behavior.

00:38:59.160 --> 00:39:01.190
And don't forget,
variability also

00:39:01.190 --> 00:39:02.780
has something to do with chance.

00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:04.640
At the end of the
day though, what

00:39:04.640 --> 00:39:07.060
all of the behavior
genetic approach

00:39:07.060 --> 00:39:10.930
is going to come down to at
the end is a single number.

00:39:10.930 --> 00:39:15.030
We have studied this trait
with adoption techniques,

00:39:15.030 --> 00:39:18.500
with looking for
genetic markers,

00:39:18.500 --> 00:39:21.780
with looking for
copy length variance.

00:39:21.780 --> 00:39:25.510
We have studied this trait
and the variability of it.

00:39:25.510 --> 00:39:28.240
And thanks to us studying
for a gazillion years,

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:34.100
we can now conclude that 53.5%
percent of the variability

00:39:34.100 --> 00:39:36.390
in this trait is heritable.

00:39:36.390 --> 00:39:39.040
You come up with this
number at the end.

00:39:39.040 --> 00:39:43.730
This trait has a
53% heritability.

00:39:43.730 --> 00:39:46.240
That's the number that
winds up coming out.

00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:49.420
Scientists report that
this or that trait

00:39:49.420 --> 00:39:53.170
has variability as
80% heritability.

00:39:53.170 --> 00:39:56.230
This is the number that
always comes out at the end.

00:39:56.230 --> 00:39:58.460
What's the heritability?

00:39:58.460 --> 00:40:02.870
Ranging somewhere
from 0% up to 100%.

00:40:02.870 --> 00:40:05.230
This is heritability.

00:40:05.230 --> 00:40:07.600
And this is absolutely critical.

00:40:07.600 --> 00:40:11.290
Because this is a truly
influential number.

00:40:11.290 --> 00:40:13.180
The one that people
come away with when

00:40:13.180 --> 00:40:17.440
they are being taught,
Oh, this trait is genetic.

00:40:17.440 --> 00:40:18.960
Those who want to
be quantitative

00:40:18.960 --> 00:40:22.520
will have been told, Whoa this
trait has 80% heritability.

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:25.340
It has 90% heritability,
all of that.

00:40:25.340 --> 00:40:28.204
And it's the wrong
interpretation.

00:40:28.204 --> 00:40:30.370
And what we're going to
spend a bunch of time on now

00:40:30.370 --> 00:40:33.740
is looking at what
heritability actually means.

00:40:33.740 --> 00:40:35.830
The heritability
number-- because it

00:40:35.830 --> 00:40:39.170
is completely different
from the everyday intuition

00:40:39.170 --> 00:40:40.080
about what it means.

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:42.070
And what it's
usually telling you

00:40:42.070 --> 00:40:46.520
is how unimportant genes are
in the deterministic way rather

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:47.780
than the other way around.

00:40:47.780 --> 00:40:48.280
OK.

00:40:48.280 --> 00:40:50.130
So what does everyone assume?

00:40:50.130 --> 00:40:52.830
What is heritability
telling you?

00:40:52.830 --> 00:40:55.630
It is telling you
how much do genes

00:40:55.630 --> 00:40:59.830
determine the average
level of this trait.

00:40:59.830 --> 00:41:04.430
You have one version of a gene,
and there's the other flavor.

00:41:04.430 --> 00:41:09.790
And they produce different
average levels of some behavior

00:41:09.790 --> 00:41:10.970
or something at the end.

00:41:10.970 --> 00:41:13.510
What heritability
is teaching you,

00:41:13.510 --> 00:41:15.570
if you've got this
completely wrong notion,

00:41:15.570 --> 00:41:17.920
it's teaching you
how much do genes

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:22.300
have to do with the average
level of that behavior,

00:41:22.300 --> 00:41:23.890
that trait, that whatever.

00:41:23.890 --> 00:41:26.700
That's not what
heritability actually means.

00:41:26.700 --> 00:41:29.600
What heritability as
a number is telling

00:41:29.600 --> 00:41:33.270
you is not what genes have
to do with the average level

00:41:33.270 --> 00:41:35.530
of the trait, it's
what genes have

00:41:35.530 --> 00:41:38.980
to do with the
degree of variability

00:41:38.980 --> 00:41:41.800
around that average.

00:41:41.800 --> 00:41:44.020
This is a point where
things immediately

00:41:44.020 --> 00:41:48.920
seem panicky and start getting
very, very complicated,

00:41:48.920 --> 00:41:49.890
all of that.

00:41:49.890 --> 00:41:51.930
We will see it's not that bad.

00:41:51.930 --> 00:41:53.890
And it's not that bad
in a very critical way.

00:42:00.730 --> 00:42:02.860
OK, simple first sense
of getting at it.

00:42:02.860 --> 00:42:06.310
Here's two populations where
you measure something or other.

00:42:06.310 --> 00:42:09.950
And these three individuals,
they come in at nine, 10, 11.

00:42:09.950 --> 00:42:12.740
And these come in at one,
10, and 19, or whatever.

00:42:12.740 --> 00:42:13.750
What's going on here?

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:14.880
You average them.

00:42:14.880 --> 00:42:17.260
They have the
exact same average.

00:42:17.260 --> 00:42:18.500
What's the difference?

00:42:18.500 --> 00:42:21.590
There's a lot more
variability around the average

00:42:21.590 --> 00:42:23.570
here than in this case.

00:42:23.570 --> 00:42:25.680
What's the wrong
idea that people

00:42:25.680 --> 00:42:28.300
have that heritability means?

00:42:28.300 --> 00:42:31.490
It's telling you
how much do genes

00:42:31.490 --> 00:42:33.990
determine the average here.

00:42:33.990 --> 00:42:35.400
That's not what it's doing.

00:42:35.400 --> 00:42:40.790
It's how much do genes determine
how much variability there is.

00:42:40.790 --> 00:42:43.830
Initially, this seems
like a very subtle point.

00:42:43.830 --> 00:42:44.912
And what's the big deal?

00:42:44.912 --> 00:42:46.370
Because at the end
of the day, it's

00:42:46.370 --> 00:42:48.660
still talking about how
important genes are.

00:42:48.660 --> 00:42:50.960
What we'll see now
is it's actually

00:42:50.960 --> 00:42:54.140
a way of seeing how less
deterministic genes are

00:42:54.140 --> 00:42:55.770
in lots of cases.

00:42:55.770 --> 00:42:59.150
So this heritability stuff,
talking about variants.

00:42:59.150 --> 00:43:01.045
Here we have an example.

00:43:06.330 --> 00:43:09.740
We've got some plant.

00:43:09.740 --> 00:43:12.280
Some plant with
some gene that comes

00:43:12.280 --> 00:43:13.960
in three different flavors.

00:43:13.960 --> 00:43:17.130
And you measure something
or other about the plant.

00:43:17.130 --> 00:43:20.500
This is how much
water it retains,

00:43:20.500 --> 00:43:22.830
or of the plant's IQ,
or something like that.

00:43:22.830 --> 00:43:25.500
You're measuring some
trait, and you're asking,

00:43:25.500 --> 00:43:28.960
Does it differ as a function
of which version of this gene

00:43:28.960 --> 00:43:29.620
you have?

00:43:29.620 --> 00:43:32.250
So you do your study,
and this is what you see.

00:43:32.250 --> 00:43:33.710
And you say, Whoa, OK.

00:43:33.710 --> 00:43:36.210
I went and looked at this
plant in a rain forest,

00:43:36.210 --> 00:43:38.730
and we identified the
genetic versions of it.

00:43:38.730 --> 00:43:42.300
And look-- very different.

00:43:42.300 --> 00:43:45.900
The gene that you have
there, knowing that,

00:43:45.900 --> 00:43:47.780
gives you a lot of
predictive power

00:43:47.780 --> 00:43:51.000
over what level of
whatever it is that you're

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:52.720
measuring this plant is.

00:43:52.720 --> 00:43:53.670
That's great.

00:43:53.670 --> 00:43:55.890
So you're going to get
your doctorate out of that,

00:43:55.890 --> 00:43:57.352
and you get some publications.

00:43:57.352 --> 00:43:59.560
And it's great, and you
finally stop being a student.

00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:00.590
And it's terrific.

00:44:00.590 --> 00:44:03.440
And meanwhile,
some individual who

00:44:03.440 --> 00:44:05.760
shares like none of
your genes in common

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:08.240
on the other side of
the planet, meanwhile

00:44:08.240 --> 00:44:11.230
there are some S-O-B who's
studying the exact same plant

00:44:11.230 --> 00:44:13.350
in the middle of
the Gobi Desert.

00:44:13.350 --> 00:44:15.710
You're sitting here in
the Amazon studying this,

00:44:15.710 --> 00:44:18.680
and here's this individual
doing the exact same kind

00:44:18.680 --> 00:44:20.690
of experiment,
saying, Oh, here we

00:44:20.690 --> 00:44:23.310
have this unlikely plant
that grows both in the Amazon

00:44:23.310 --> 00:44:24.390
and the Gobi Desert.

00:44:24.390 --> 00:44:26.720
But here we have this, and
we're studying this here.

00:44:26.720 --> 00:44:28.320
And what am I studying?

00:44:28.320 --> 00:44:31.160
I'm studying those
three variants.

00:44:31.160 --> 00:44:33.610
Those three variants
of this gene.

00:44:33.610 --> 00:44:38.200
And I'm asking do they
influence plant IQ?

00:44:38.200 --> 00:44:40.770
The same thing that you
were asking over here.

00:44:40.770 --> 00:44:43.420
And that individual
was doing their study,

00:44:43.420 --> 00:44:46.910
and they see that yes,
indeed, the gene influences

00:44:46.910 --> 00:44:48.450
what version that you have.

00:44:48.450 --> 00:44:51.270
And here you had A,
B, and C. And here's

00:44:51.270 --> 00:44:55.330
what they see when
they measure plant IQ.

00:44:55.330 --> 00:44:57.550
And it looks like that.

00:44:57.550 --> 00:44:59.130
And what do they conclude?

00:44:59.130 --> 00:45:00.660
Whoa, look at that.

00:45:00.660 --> 00:45:02.700
Knowing what version
of the gene you

00:45:02.700 --> 00:45:05.290
have gives me enormous
predictive power

00:45:05.290 --> 00:45:08.890
in predicting what the
plant IQ is going to be.

00:45:08.890 --> 00:45:12.840
And then catastrophically,
tragically, the two of you

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:15.370
meet each other and
discover that you're both

00:45:15.370 --> 00:45:16.820
researching the same plant.

00:45:16.820 --> 00:45:21.040
And you look at your
numbers, and your heart

00:45:21.040 --> 00:45:22.400
breaks at that point.

00:45:22.400 --> 00:45:25.790
Because you look at these,
and what's going on here?

00:45:25.790 --> 00:45:26.760
What's going on?

00:45:26.760 --> 00:45:29.220
Let's translate this
notion of heritability,

00:45:29.220 --> 00:45:30.510
and variance, and all of that.

00:45:30.510 --> 00:45:33.870
Let's translate it into
a very simple question

00:45:33.870 --> 00:45:37.360
you can ask, translating
all of this in English.

00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:43.520
You're interested in what this
gene has to do with plant IQ.

00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:46.970
And you're allowed to find
out one piece of information.

00:45:46.970 --> 00:45:52.280
You could know whether the
plant has version A, B, or C,

00:45:52.280 --> 00:45:55.320
or you could know
whether the plant is

00:45:55.320 --> 00:45:58.250
growing in the Amazon
or the Gobi Desert.

00:45:58.250 --> 00:46:01.290
Which piece of information
is going to give you

00:46:01.290 --> 00:46:03.890
more predictive power?

00:46:03.890 --> 00:46:07.490
And what you wind up seeing
here is if you can either

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:10.240
know this or the
environment, you

00:46:10.240 --> 00:46:12.200
want to know what
the environment is.

00:46:12.200 --> 00:46:19.050
The variability-- plant IQ could
come in at 98, 100, 102, eight,

00:46:19.050 --> 00:46:21.340
10, and 12.

00:46:21.340 --> 00:46:25.020
Far more of the variability
in those six numbers

00:46:25.020 --> 00:46:27.420
is explained by what
environment it's

00:46:27.420 --> 00:46:31.430
going on in rather than
the genetic difference.

00:46:31.430 --> 00:46:34.030
That's what heritability
is telling you.

00:46:34.030 --> 00:46:36.680
And in a study like
this, it would tell you

00:46:36.680 --> 00:46:40.420
that the heritability number
is actually quite low.

00:46:40.420 --> 00:46:45.120
Because the amount of variation
due to this is far less

00:46:45.120 --> 00:46:48.590
explained by the gene
type than whether it's

00:46:48.590 --> 00:46:51.700
the Amazon or the Gobi Desert.

00:46:51.700 --> 00:46:53.710
So that's a first pass at it.

00:46:53.710 --> 00:46:55.940
Why is this really important?

00:46:55.940 --> 00:46:57.810
For the following reason.

00:46:57.810 --> 00:47:00.460
You're a scientist,
and you are trying

00:47:00.460 --> 00:47:05.380
to understand how A, B,
and C influence plant IQ.

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:07.740
And you come up with
something nutty and stupid

00:47:07.740 --> 00:47:09.690
like saying, Well,
I would like to be

00:47:09.690 --> 00:47:13.750
able to do field seasons in both
the Amazon and the Gobi Desert.

00:47:13.750 --> 00:47:16.830
And your advisor will
say, or all of your elders

00:47:16.830 --> 00:47:19.630
will say something like,
No, you can't do that.

00:47:19.630 --> 00:47:24.450
Because that's just-- you're
not controlling for environment.

00:47:24.450 --> 00:47:29.300
You're not studying it in only
one controlled environment.

00:47:29.300 --> 00:47:31.550
You can't go to-- they're
such different ecosystems,

00:47:31.550 --> 00:47:32.230
all of that.

00:47:32.230 --> 00:47:34.970
Pick one and go study it there.

00:47:34.970 --> 00:47:37.140
And what you do is
you go study it there.

00:47:37.140 --> 00:47:39.010
And as a result of
just studying it here,

00:47:39.010 --> 00:47:41.800
you come away thinking
that virtually

00:47:41.800 --> 00:47:45.260
all of the variability
is explained by genes.

00:47:45.260 --> 00:47:47.540
What have you just done?

00:47:47.540 --> 00:47:51.100
You explicitly have
designed your experiment

00:47:51.100 --> 00:47:54.910
so that you can't detect
the environmental role

00:47:54.910 --> 00:47:56.820
in determining that trait.

00:47:56.820 --> 00:48:01.170
What counts as setting up the
experiment as the right way

00:48:01.170 --> 00:48:03.180
for people who think
about this sort of thing,

00:48:03.180 --> 00:48:05.450
standard sort of
approaches to experiment,

00:48:05.450 --> 00:48:10.640
what counts as doing a good
job by definition, what you're

00:48:10.640 --> 00:48:14.530
doing is biasing towards
thinking the genetic input

00:48:14.530 --> 00:48:17.370
is more important
than it actually is.

00:48:17.370 --> 00:48:20.660
Because scientists don't
decide to study this trait

00:48:20.660 --> 00:48:21.700
in two different places.

00:48:21.700 --> 00:48:23.800
You don't decide
to do a study where

00:48:23.800 --> 00:48:27.570
you're looking at some trait
in both rats and ocelots,

00:48:27.570 --> 00:48:28.140
or something.

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:32.930
Look, pick one species.

00:48:32.930 --> 00:48:34.990
Maybe even pick just one gender.

00:48:34.990 --> 00:48:36.290
Pick one environment.

00:48:36.290 --> 00:48:38.980
Don't have your rats in one room
where the air conditioning is

00:48:38.980 --> 00:48:42.480
going nonstop and the other
room you're barbecuing stuff.

00:48:42.480 --> 00:48:45.370
Control for environment.

00:48:45.370 --> 00:48:46.870
And by definition,
if you've done

00:48:46.870 --> 00:48:49.172
the nice, careful,
responsible thing

00:48:49.172 --> 00:48:51.630
that a scientist's supposed to
do doing this sort of thing,

00:48:51.630 --> 00:48:53.300
you control for environment.

00:48:53.300 --> 00:48:55.250
What have you just done?

00:48:55.250 --> 00:48:57.270
You have just
removed your ability

00:48:57.270 --> 00:48:59.720
to see the role of environment.

00:48:59.720 --> 00:49:03.010
And you have just artificially
inflated how important

00:49:03.010 --> 00:49:04.690
you think the genes are.

00:49:04.690 --> 00:49:06.410
OK, let's take a
five minute break.

00:49:06.410 --> 00:49:08.580
We are going to look at
this in a lot more detail.

00:49:08.580 --> 00:49:11.450
Do not freak out if this is
not immediately intuitively

00:49:11.450 --> 00:49:13.010
obvious.

00:49:13.010 --> 00:49:14.940
Questions that just came up.

00:49:14.940 --> 00:49:16.740
The first one is
pointing out one

00:49:16.740 --> 00:49:19.840
of those where I probably
should have actually taught

00:49:19.840 --> 00:49:21.340
something clearer.

00:49:21.340 --> 00:49:25.460
What are you talking about with
proteins being different sizes?

00:49:25.460 --> 00:49:27.880
How do you figure out
proteins are different sizes?

00:49:27.880 --> 00:49:29.920
And the answer is
you make them stand

00:49:29.920 --> 00:49:31.940
against the wall in their
bedroom with a ruler,

00:49:31.940 --> 00:49:33.080
and you mark it there.

00:49:33.080 --> 00:49:35.080
And then you see if
they differ in size.

00:49:35.080 --> 00:49:37.940
Or if that doesn't
work, what you do is you

00:49:37.940 --> 00:49:40.560
use various
biochemical techniques.

00:49:40.560 --> 00:49:44.850
You basically make
something akin

00:49:44.850 --> 00:49:48.810
to a thick, homogeneous
soup of something or other.

00:49:48.810 --> 00:49:51.800
And you put the two different
versions of the protein

00:49:51.800 --> 00:49:54.540
in there, and essentially
you sit and wait

00:49:54.540 --> 00:49:57.980
and see how far they sink down.

00:49:57.980 --> 00:50:01.730
And the one that's heavier is
going to sink down further.

00:50:01.730 --> 00:50:05.090
Anyone who knowns about gels
and the electrophoresis,

00:50:05.090 --> 00:50:06.650
that's insanely simplified.

00:50:06.650 --> 00:50:09.020
But that's basically
the notion of it.

00:50:09.020 --> 00:50:10.840
Put them where they
move through something

00:50:10.840 --> 00:50:13.130
as a function of
their weight, gravity,

00:50:13.130 --> 00:50:15.750
and you could then pick
up size differences.

00:50:15.750 --> 00:50:17.410
The other good
question that was asked

00:50:17.410 --> 00:50:20.810
is, What did you just say
in the last 10 minutes?

00:50:20.810 --> 00:50:25.430
This is very difficult. This
is an extremely subtle point.

00:50:25.430 --> 00:50:27.370
And I'm going to hammer
it in over, and over,

00:50:27.370 --> 00:50:29.720
again here, in
sections, all of that.

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:31.330
Why is it so important?

00:50:31.330 --> 00:50:35.000
Because number one, this
is a number, heritability,

00:50:35.000 --> 00:50:37.890
that the general lay
public comes away

00:50:37.890 --> 00:50:40.550
with interpreting
incompletely wrongly.

00:50:40.550 --> 00:50:43.690
And number two, the vast
majority of scientists,

00:50:43.690 --> 00:50:46.500
when they're working in this
field of behavior genetics,

00:50:46.500 --> 00:50:50.390
design their experiments
so that by definition, they

00:50:50.390 --> 00:50:52.780
are eliminating
all sorts of realms

00:50:52.780 --> 00:50:55.710
of environmental influences.

00:50:55.710 --> 00:50:57.440
So going back to this here.

00:50:57.440 --> 00:51:00.620
So here we see once again
this simple question.

00:51:00.620 --> 00:51:04.090
Use this one over and over
translating all this theory

00:51:04.090 --> 00:51:05.750
in variation and stuff.

00:51:05.750 --> 00:51:08.410
Always translates into
the same question.

00:51:08.410 --> 00:51:12.040
I can find out what type,
