01:03:46.140 --> 01:03:47.430
there, PKU.

01:03:47.430 --> 01:03:48.690
Phenylketonuria.

01:03:48.690 --> 01:03:51.430
Just to remind you, do not
worry about the details.

01:03:51.430 --> 01:03:55.870
It's this disease where normally
there's this thing in your body

01:03:55.870 --> 01:03:57.720
which would be
toxic to your brain

01:03:57.720 --> 01:04:01.060
unless it's turned
into something else.

01:04:01.060 --> 01:04:04.540
And this is the
enzyme-- the protein,

01:04:04.540 --> 01:04:06.310
and thus coded for
by a gene-- this

01:04:06.310 --> 01:04:08.540
is the enzyme that
turns the scary version

01:04:08.540 --> 01:04:09.720
into the safe version.

01:04:09.720 --> 01:04:13.100
And in PKU, you have a
mutation in this enzyme,

01:04:13.100 --> 01:04:14.520
it's not doing its job.

01:04:14.520 --> 01:04:18.950
The scary version builds up and
wipes out your nervous system.

01:04:18.950 --> 01:04:20.300
That looks bad.

01:04:20.300 --> 01:04:23.440
And what we've got now
is a trait where you're

01:04:23.440 --> 01:04:26.490
going to say, well, let's see.

01:04:26.490 --> 01:04:29.640
I am very interested
in knowing, being

01:04:29.640 --> 01:04:33.060
able to predict whether or not
this person has a fairly normal

01:04:33.060 --> 01:04:35.640
looking brain or whether
it looks like Swiss cheese.

01:04:35.640 --> 01:04:38.010
Do I want to know whether
or not they're growing up

01:04:38.010 --> 01:04:40.649
in Idaho versus Montana?

01:04:40.649 --> 01:04:42.440
Or do I want to know
whether or not they've

01:04:42.440 --> 01:04:44.697
got a mutation in this enzyme?

01:04:44.697 --> 01:04:46.280
Obviously, you want
to know if there's

01:04:46.280 --> 01:04:47.600
a mutation in the enzyme.

01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:50.740
Seemingly, heritability is 100%.

01:04:50.740 --> 01:04:52.890
But now you do
something which people

01:04:52.890 --> 01:04:55.960
have been doing for people with
PKU for a couple of decades

01:04:55.960 --> 01:04:56.460
now.

01:04:56.460 --> 01:05:01.390
Which is, you put little labels
on bottles of food and stuff

01:05:01.390 --> 01:05:06.580
saying, if this food contains
the scary bad news thing.

01:05:06.580 --> 01:05:09.640
And if you have
PKU, if you simply

01:05:09.640 --> 01:05:13.910
don't eat food that contains
that-- if you have what's

01:05:13.910 --> 01:05:16.840
called a fennel
alanine free diet--

01:05:16.840 --> 01:05:19.960
you don't get your brain
looking like Swiss cheese.

01:05:19.960 --> 01:05:21.320
What have you got there?

01:05:21.320 --> 01:05:24.220
You've just put in an
environmental influence

01:05:24.220 --> 01:05:27.720
that has reduced
heritability down to zero.

01:05:27.720 --> 01:05:31.520
This is a case where we've got
something like this looking.

01:05:31.520 --> 01:05:34.850
And here we're measuring is,
like, the Swiss cheese index,

01:05:34.850 --> 01:05:36.210
or whatever of the brain.

01:05:36.210 --> 01:05:40.350
And what we've got here is, this
is an environment where people

01:05:40.350 --> 01:05:44.190
know how much of the stuff there
is in different types of food

01:05:44.190 --> 01:05:45.440
and don't eat it.

01:05:45.440 --> 01:05:47.960
A simple environmental--
not so simple--

01:05:47.960 --> 01:05:50.050
but an environmental
intervention.

01:05:50.050 --> 01:05:52.900
A behavioral change
in the environment.

01:05:52.900 --> 01:05:56.760
And you've just reduced
heritability from 100% to 0%.

01:05:56.760 --> 01:05:59.160
So that is a dramatic version.

01:05:59.160 --> 01:06:04.010
Now, let's look at a version
of a real life example of this.

01:06:04.010 --> 01:06:08.960
This would be with-- I think
I've already put this one up.

01:06:21.194 --> 01:06:24.630
OK, does this work
familiar by now?

01:06:24.630 --> 01:06:25.500
No.

01:06:25.500 --> 01:06:26.950
OK, that was at Thanksgiving.

01:06:26.950 --> 01:06:27.450
OK.

01:06:27.450 --> 01:06:31.200
What we've got here is a
gene that's got something

01:06:31.200 --> 01:06:32.220
to do with depression.

01:06:32.220 --> 01:06:34.670
It's a gene that has something
to do with neurotransmitter

01:06:34.670 --> 01:06:35.800
serotonin.

01:06:35.800 --> 01:06:38.010
Details don't matter,
they will come later.

01:06:38.010 --> 01:06:40.780
But the gene comes in
two different flavors.

01:06:40.780 --> 01:06:43.510
And one version of it,
based on everything

01:06:43.510 --> 01:06:45.700
that's known from
laboratory animals,

01:06:45.700 --> 01:06:48.810
one version should be
the kind that predisposes

01:06:48.810 --> 01:06:51.240
you more towards depression.

01:06:51.240 --> 01:06:54.680
So, in this incredibly
important study

01:06:54.680 --> 01:06:56.390
that was done a
number of years ago,

01:06:56.390 --> 01:06:59.190
a guy named Caspi, Duke
University, and colleagues,

01:06:59.190 --> 01:07:04.000
they had been studying 17,000
people basically from birth

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:06.670
up to age 25 or
so in New Zealand.

01:07:06.670 --> 01:07:08.200
And who knows why
in New Zealand,

01:07:08.200 --> 01:07:11.310
but studying them there,
and following and asking.

01:07:11.310 --> 01:07:14.180
They took blood so they know
the whole genetic profiles.

01:07:14.180 --> 01:07:17.330
And looking at, among
other things, by age 25,

01:07:17.330 --> 01:07:19.540
does the person have
major depression or not.

01:07:19.540 --> 01:07:22.370
Have they had an
episode of depression.

01:07:22.370 --> 01:07:26.420
And now let's go look at which
version of this gene they have.

01:07:26.420 --> 01:07:28.640
And what would everything
predict from all the animal

01:07:28.640 --> 01:07:31.770
studies, which is you have
the bad version of the gene

01:07:31.770 --> 01:07:34.930
and you're, as a human,
going to have a higher

01:07:34.930 --> 01:07:37.320
chance of having a depression.

01:07:37.320 --> 01:07:39.340
That's not what the
data looked like.

01:07:39.340 --> 01:07:43.170
Instead, it was one
of those "it depends."

01:07:43.170 --> 01:07:46.090
It depends on the environment.

01:07:46.090 --> 01:07:48.510
What you saw was,
it all depended

01:07:48.510 --> 01:07:54.220
on how many major childhood
stressors there were.

01:07:54.220 --> 01:07:57.680
Loss of a parent, divorce,
abuse, some such thing.

01:07:57.680 --> 01:08:00.700
And the absence of
any of those, this

01:08:00.700 --> 01:08:02.670
was the rate of depression
in the people having

01:08:02.670 --> 01:08:03.980
the good version.

01:08:03.980 --> 01:08:06.820
And throw in one childhood
trauma, two of them,

01:08:06.820 --> 01:08:10.690
three of them, and the
incidence is going up slightly.

01:08:10.690 --> 01:08:13.540
Now, you've got the bad
version of the gene.

01:08:13.540 --> 01:08:16.630
And it puts you
more at risk only

01:08:16.630 --> 01:08:19.010
in certain types
of environments.

01:08:19.010 --> 01:08:22.330
So here we have a great gene
environment interaction.

01:08:22.330 --> 01:08:24.130
That's something
straight out of this one.

01:08:24.130 --> 01:08:25.935
You're saying well,
what does this gene

01:08:25.935 --> 01:08:27.560
have to do with the
risk of depression?

01:08:27.560 --> 01:08:29.510
And the answer is, it depends.

01:08:29.510 --> 01:08:32.710
It depends on what your
childhood environment was like.

01:08:32.710 --> 01:08:35.779
But now, one additional detail
showing that this is actually

01:08:35.779 --> 01:08:36.810
a case of this.

01:08:36.810 --> 01:08:38.830
One that just gets
ignored whenever

01:08:38.830 --> 01:08:41.620
people talk about the
study because it's cool,

01:08:41.620 --> 01:08:43.542
but it's actually not
all that important.

01:08:43.542 --> 01:08:46.000
OK, so here's the people with
the good version of the gene,

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:47.292
but it makes this point though.

01:08:47.292 --> 01:08:49.416
You've got the good version,
and they're down here.

01:08:49.416 --> 01:08:50.920
And you know what's
going to happen,

01:08:50.920 --> 01:08:52.919
the bad version is going
to be exactly the same.

01:08:52.919 --> 01:08:57.800
But you look at the data
closely, and in the absence,

01:08:57.800 --> 01:09:01.370
the bad version is actually
a little bit protective

01:09:01.370 --> 01:09:04.290
from depression versus
the quote "good version."

01:09:04.290 --> 01:09:06.140
What have you just
discovered there?

01:09:06.140 --> 01:09:07.859
It's one of these.

01:09:07.859 --> 01:09:10.840
This is a radical gene
environment interaction.

01:09:10.840 --> 01:09:14.797
Not only is it the case that,
does this put you more at risk?

01:09:14.797 --> 01:09:16.380
Well, that depends
on the environment.

01:09:16.380 --> 01:09:19.591
Depending on your environment,
it could put you less at risk.

01:09:19.591 --> 01:09:21.340
This one is not a big
deal because there's

01:09:21.340 --> 01:09:22.914
a tiny difference.

01:09:22.914 --> 01:09:24.330
There's no reason
to pay attention

01:09:24.330 --> 01:09:27.580
to it, other than just sort of
pointing it out pedagogically.

01:09:27.580 --> 01:09:31.149
But this is an amazing
example where this can

01:09:31.149 --> 01:09:33.140
go in the opposite direction.

01:09:33.140 --> 01:09:37.560
This is a hugely important
gene environment interaction.

01:09:37.560 --> 01:09:40.930
So what all of this begins
to set you up for is,

01:09:40.930 --> 01:09:43.800
you've forgot this
heritability number.

01:09:43.800 --> 01:09:46.350
And people come away
constantly thinking about,

01:09:46.350 --> 01:09:49.859
it's telling you about how much
the average level of a trait

01:09:49.859 --> 01:09:51.250
is determined by genes.

01:09:51.250 --> 01:09:54.109
It's instead telling you
how much the variability.

01:09:54.109 --> 01:09:57.320
What that means, thus, by
definition, that there's

01:09:57.320 --> 01:10:00.260
all sorts of nutty
counter-intuitive things going

01:10:00.260 --> 01:10:03.610
on, where earrings are totally
heritable and number of fingers

01:10:03.610 --> 01:10:04.485
are not.

01:10:04.485 --> 01:10:09.070
What that tells you is, by
definition, the way experiments

01:10:09.070 --> 01:10:12.510
are set up to make things nice
and clean and interpretable,

01:10:12.510 --> 01:10:16.780
scientists typically remove
environmental variability.

01:10:16.780 --> 01:10:19.430
Scientists typically
artificially

01:10:19.430 --> 01:10:24.470
have boosted up the seeming
heritability of a trait.

01:10:24.470 --> 01:10:26.160
What does that tell you?

01:10:26.160 --> 01:10:30.220
The more different environments
you study a trait in,

01:10:30.220 --> 01:10:32.860
the lower the heritability
is going to be.

01:10:32.860 --> 01:10:34.880
Because you are
going to be getting

01:10:34.880 --> 01:10:38.940
more and more opportunities
for things to be different.

01:10:38.940 --> 01:10:42.590
More opportunities to be
able to say, it depends.

01:10:42.590 --> 01:10:44.670
It depends on which environment.

01:10:44.670 --> 01:10:47.660
We've just studied it in
99 different environments,

01:10:47.660 --> 01:10:49.730
and it always looks like this.

01:10:49.730 --> 01:10:51.680
No difference by
environment, and genes

01:10:51.680 --> 01:10:53.150
always make a huge difference.

01:10:53.150 --> 01:10:56.330
And then you go out and,
before dying of fatigue,

01:10:56.330 --> 01:10:58.500
you study it in the
hundredth environment,

01:10:58.500 --> 01:11:01.320
and it now looks like
this sort of thing.

01:11:01.320 --> 01:11:05.895
What you've just learned is,
this is a "it depends" example.

01:11:05.895 --> 01:11:09.150
And the more environments
you study something in,

01:11:09.150 --> 01:11:11.840
the lower heritability
is going to be.

01:11:11.840 --> 01:11:14.940
Translating that into
English, the more environments

01:11:14.940 --> 01:11:18.010
you study a genetically
influenced trait,

01:11:18.010 --> 01:11:20.230
the less interesting
and important

01:11:20.230 --> 01:11:22.152
the genes are going to be.

01:11:22.152 --> 01:11:23.800
The less interesting
and important

01:11:23.800 --> 01:11:25.910
they're going to
be in answering,

01:11:25.910 --> 01:11:28.402
what does this gene have
to do with whatever?

01:11:28.402 --> 01:11:30.110
And what we're seeing
over and over again

01:11:30.110 --> 01:11:32.400
is, the only way to answer
it over and over again

01:11:32.400 --> 01:11:34.110
is, it's going to
be an "it depends."

01:11:34.110 --> 01:11:35.510
It depends on the environment.

01:11:35.510 --> 01:11:38.960
Ultimately-- as I said a
little while ago-- ultimately,

01:11:38.960 --> 01:11:43.530
it winds up being meaningless
to ask what a gene does.

01:11:43.530 --> 01:11:47.070
Ultimately, the only
really truly scientific way

01:11:47.070 --> 01:11:48.760
you can answer a
question like that

01:11:48.760 --> 01:11:54.120
is, what does this gene do in
this particular environment?

01:11:54.120 --> 01:11:57.057
People make this big deal out
of oh, genes do something,

01:11:57.057 --> 01:11:58.140
environments do something.

01:11:58.140 --> 01:12:00.920
And every now and
then, hooray, they

01:12:00.920 --> 01:12:04.640
interact in some exciting way
in teaching the gene environment

01:12:04.640 --> 01:12:06.660
interaction cliche,
that's what's

01:12:06.660 --> 01:12:08.640
happening every single time.

01:12:08.640 --> 01:12:11.130
And that winds up
being the basis of that

01:12:11.130 --> 01:12:13.580
quote from Paul Ehrlich
in this department

01:12:13.580 --> 01:12:16.120
that I put on the
handout, which is great,

01:12:16.120 --> 01:12:20.790
summarizes this entire
point, asking whether genes

01:12:20.790 --> 01:12:23.580
or environment have more
to do with some trait

01:12:23.580 --> 01:12:26.720
is akin to asking whether
height or length have more

01:12:26.720 --> 01:12:28.950
to do with the volume
of a rectangle.

01:12:28.950 --> 01:12:30.630
They're inseparable.

01:12:30.630 --> 01:12:33.430
There is no such thing
as a gene influence

01:12:33.430 --> 01:12:37.970
outside the context of an
environmental interaction.

01:12:37.970 --> 01:12:38.900
OK.

01:12:38.900 --> 01:12:41.390
Let's look more at
what this looks like.

01:12:41.390 --> 01:12:43.740
Here, this being
one great example.

01:12:43.740 --> 01:12:45.900
And this being this iconic one.

01:12:45.900 --> 01:12:50.520
And this is a finding that
is destined to be, like,

01:12:50.520 --> 01:12:52.390
the most important
in the last quarter

01:12:52.390 --> 01:12:54.640
century in biological
psychiatry.

01:12:54.640 --> 01:12:57.330
It is the most
powerful demonstration

01:12:57.330 --> 01:13:03.200
in the realm of abnormal human
behavior of what your genotype

01:13:03.200 --> 01:13:04.830
has to do with your behavior.

01:13:04.830 --> 01:13:08.700
The most amazing, logical,
intuitively reasonable

01:13:08.700 --> 01:13:11.310
demonstration of "it depends."

01:13:11.310 --> 01:13:14.900
It depends on how stressful
the childhood environment was.

01:13:14.900 --> 01:13:16.500
Really great.

01:13:16.500 --> 01:13:18.220
Bringing things
back to last weeks

01:13:18.220 --> 01:13:20.900
sort of molecular
lectures, people already

01:13:20.900 --> 01:13:22.550
know who study this.

01:13:22.550 --> 01:13:26.150
The two different versions
of the gene, certain classes

01:13:26.150 --> 01:13:31.540
of stress hormones interact with
the two versions differently.

01:13:31.540 --> 01:13:35.070
When stress hormone levels
aren't particularly raised,

01:13:35.070 --> 01:13:37.910
that difference isn't
being manifested.

01:13:37.910 --> 01:13:40.210
The more of a history
of stress-- and it's

01:13:40.210 --> 01:13:42.890
obviously more mechanical,
more complicated

01:13:42.890 --> 01:13:46.650
than just how much you're
exposed to-- but the promoters,

01:13:46.650 --> 01:13:49.380
the variation here
is in the promoters.

01:13:49.380 --> 01:13:51.760
The promoters
interact differently

01:13:51.760 --> 01:13:54.730
with those glucocorticoid
stress hormones.

01:13:54.730 --> 01:13:57.020
In the absence of the
glucocorticoid stress hormones,

01:13:57.020 --> 01:14:00.110
because in the absence
of something exciting,

01:14:00.110 --> 01:14:03.700
your genetic difference
makes no difference.

01:14:03.700 --> 01:14:07.872
So we've just translated
an epidemiological answer--

01:14:07.872 --> 01:14:09.830
what does this gene have
to do with depression?

01:14:09.830 --> 01:14:11.010
It depends.

01:14:11.010 --> 01:14:13.930
It depends on your
childhood stress history.

01:14:13.930 --> 01:14:17.797
We've just translated that into
last week's molecular biology,

01:14:17.797 --> 01:14:20.380
what does this genetic variance
have to do with whether or not

01:14:20.380 --> 01:14:21.213
you have depression?

01:14:21.213 --> 01:14:22.540
It depends.

01:14:22.540 --> 01:14:26.730
It depends on how much childhood
exposure to glucocorticoids

01:14:26.730 --> 01:14:27.710
you had.

01:14:27.710 --> 01:14:30.530
So we've just leaped
from analyzing this

01:14:30.530 --> 01:14:33.260
in the context of this
field, to translating that

01:14:33.260 --> 01:14:34.780
into last week.

01:14:34.780 --> 01:14:36.720
And translating that
into the endocrine

01:14:36.720 --> 01:14:40.390
lectures that are going to come
next week, beginning to show,

01:14:40.390 --> 01:14:42.150
OK, you're an epidemiologist.

01:14:42.150 --> 01:14:45.077
The answer is, what
sort of environment?

01:14:45.077 --> 01:14:46.160
You're an endocrinologist.

01:14:46.160 --> 01:14:49.690
The answer is, well, the
hormonal environment.

01:14:49.690 --> 01:14:52.570
Whether you define it,
it's the same punch line.

01:14:52.570 --> 01:14:53.830
It depends.

01:14:53.830 --> 01:14:55.950
It depends on the environment.

01:14:55.950 --> 01:14:59.320
So this is the best,
most amazing example

01:14:59.320 --> 01:15:01.040
of this in all of psychiatry.

01:15:01.040 --> 01:15:04.400
Except, these guys--
Caspian colleagues--

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:07.380
measured something
else and they got just

01:15:07.380 --> 01:15:09.760
as bestest of an
answer for that.

01:15:09.760 --> 01:15:13.790
Which is, they looked at
another gene that has variation.

01:15:13.790 --> 01:15:15.840
One we will hear
about down the line.

01:15:15.840 --> 01:15:19.270
A gene called MAO,
monoamine oxidase.

01:15:19.270 --> 01:15:23.320
All we need to know right now
is, a gazillion animal studies

01:15:23.320 --> 01:15:26.420
suggest that one
version of the gene

01:15:26.420 --> 01:15:30.420
predisposes more towards
aggression than the other.

01:15:30.420 --> 01:15:31.320
Whoa.

01:15:31.320 --> 01:15:34.070
So they've got
17,000 people who've

01:15:34.070 --> 01:15:36.350
just had 25 years
worth of opportunity

01:15:36.350 --> 01:15:38.560
to be aggressive or not,
and they got the genes.

01:15:38.560 --> 01:15:42.750
And now they ask the question,
rather than at age 25,

01:15:42.750 --> 01:15:45.300
has this person ever had a
major clinical depression?

01:15:45.300 --> 01:15:48.520
Now they ask, at age
25, has this person ever

01:15:48.520 --> 01:15:50.560
been in trouble with
the law for some sort

01:15:50.560 --> 01:15:53.030
of antisocial behavior?

01:15:53.030 --> 01:15:55.180
Antisocial behavior
is the new jargon

01:15:55.180 --> 01:15:58.550
for what used to be called
sociopathic behavior.

01:15:58.550 --> 01:16:01.220
Has this person been
in trouble with the law

01:16:01.220 --> 01:16:03.640
for sociopathic
behavior, anti-social.

01:16:03.640 --> 01:16:07.670
And does it vary depending on
which version of the MAO gene

01:16:07.670 --> 01:16:08.300
you have?

01:16:08.300 --> 01:16:11.170
And what you get is,
not only is the answer

01:16:11.170 --> 01:16:14.690
"it depends," the
graph is basically

01:16:14.690 --> 01:16:16.460
identical to this one.

01:16:16.460 --> 01:16:19.280
It's superimposable, the
magnitude of the effect.

01:16:19.280 --> 01:16:21.920
What was this in that case?

01:16:21.920 --> 01:16:26.280
Whether or not you had, and how
severe your child history was,

01:16:26.280 --> 01:16:27.580
of abuse.

01:16:27.580 --> 01:16:30.330
The more childhood
abuse you had, the more

01:16:30.330 --> 01:16:32.930
having the wrong
version of the gene

01:16:32.930 --> 01:16:35.870
increased your odds of
having anti-social aggressive

01:16:35.870 --> 01:16:37.290
behavior.

01:16:37.290 --> 01:16:41.240
Once again, a major
dramatic "it depends."

01:16:41.240 --> 01:16:42.345
And it's stunning.

01:16:42.345 --> 01:16:43.970
You look at these
two different papers,

01:16:43.970 --> 01:16:47.190
both were published in
"Science" a couple years apart.

01:16:47.190 --> 01:16:48.940
Landmark studies, all of that.

01:16:48.940 --> 01:16:52.580
And the two graphs really
are virtually superimposable.

01:16:52.580 --> 01:16:54.380
The same magnitude of effects.

01:16:54.380 --> 01:16:55.810
The same answer.

01:16:55.810 --> 01:16:58.340
It depends on your childhood.

01:16:58.340 --> 01:17:00.520
So that is a very
strong example.

01:17:00.520 --> 01:17:05.570
Next one, another one, now you
go back to this gene difference

01:17:05.570 --> 01:17:07.920
with the serotonin,
the depression world.

01:17:07.920 --> 01:17:11.640
And now you study it in monkeys
and the variation there,

01:17:11.640 --> 01:17:14.930
there is a variation in
brain chemistry related

01:17:14.930 --> 01:17:16.940
to depression, all
of that depending

01:17:16.940 --> 01:17:20.690
on how stressful the
monkey's childhood was.

01:17:20.690 --> 01:17:23.100
Same exact sort of finding.

01:17:23.100 --> 01:17:24.180
What else?

01:17:24.180 --> 01:17:26.560
Now when you begin to
look at-- going back

01:17:26.560 --> 01:17:30.760
to that world of dopamine
receptors and thrill

01:17:30.760 --> 01:17:34.290
seeking and all of that--
and what you look at

01:17:34.290 --> 01:17:37.100
there is variability
in a certain type

01:17:37.100 --> 01:17:39.580
of different dopamine
receptor gene.

01:17:39.580 --> 01:17:41.780
And what you find
there is, if you

01:17:41.780 --> 01:17:44.020
