01:21:12.567 --> 01:21:13.900
I don't know why I show up here.

01:21:13.900 --> 01:21:15.316
I should be doing
one or the other

01:21:15.316 --> 01:21:18.250
and some sort of environment
interaction thing.

01:21:18.250 --> 01:21:19.840
So yeah, breastfeeding.

01:21:19.840 --> 01:21:20.420
OK.

01:21:20.420 --> 01:21:23.770
So one more example, a
very interesting one.

01:21:23.770 --> 01:21:26.750
And this is one that has at
some point or other, I'd bet,

01:21:26.750 --> 01:21:29.500
been pertinent to every
single person in this room.

01:21:29.500 --> 01:21:32.310
Which is, there's another
genetic difference

01:21:32.310 --> 01:21:36.240
that has something to do with
a certain cognitive aptitude.

01:21:36.240 --> 01:21:38.780
And this one
everybody knows about.

01:21:38.780 --> 01:21:41.300
And this one is as follows.

01:21:41.300 --> 01:21:44.610
If you have-- there's two
different versions of this sort

01:21:44.610 --> 01:21:48.290
of genetic picture
and they're associated

01:21:48.290 --> 01:21:50.300
with different
levels of aptitude

01:21:50.300 --> 01:21:52.010
in this particular
cognitive realm--

01:21:52.010 --> 01:21:55.800
this is not a world any more
of one single gene at a time.

01:21:55.800 --> 01:21:57.455
FAD2, any of these.

01:21:57.455 --> 01:22:00.020
This instead is talking
about a whole bunch of genes.

01:22:00.020 --> 01:22:04.130
If you have a Y
chromosome or not.

01:22:04.130 --> 01:22:06.330
If you are male or female.

01:22:06.330 --> 01:22:07.810
A genetic trait.

01:22:07.810 --> 01:22:10.150
And what is the thing
that has been demonstrated

01:22:10.150 --> 01:22:12.080
most consistently
in the literature

01:22:12.080 --> 01:22:14.120
forever and ever
and ever in terms

01:22:14.120 --> 01:22:17.580
of a gender difference in
a cognitive skill in math

01:22:17.580 --> 01:22:18.840
performance.

01:22:18.840 --> 01:22:20.530
That has come through endlessly.

01:22:20.530 --> 01:22:22.790
I've already talked
about it the other week.

01:22:22.790 --> 01:22:26.090
A small difference in the
average median performance

01:22:26.090 --> 01:22:29.520
on junior high school
old Johns Hopkins

01:22:29.520 --> 01:22:32.410
superstar kids taking the SATs.

01:22:32.410 --> 01:22:35.330
But a big difference in the tail
at the end, high performance,

01:22:35.330 --> 01:22:36.120
all of that.

01:22:36.120 --> 01:22:39.090
This comes up in
endless, endless studies.

01:22:39.090 --> 01:22:42.200
This comes up with kids
at fairly young ages.

01:22:42.200 --> 01:22:45.420
There is this gender difference
on the average-- yes, we're

01:22:45.420 --> 01:22:48.220
saying on the average, don't
forget, you say on the average

01:22:48.220 --> 01:22:50.910
before you even ignore that--
you say on the average,

01:22:50.910 --> 01:22:53.630
boys are better at
math than girls.

01:22:53.630 --> 01:22:55.760
Men are better at
math than women.

01:22:55.760 --> 01:22:58.810
Male plants in the
Gobi desert are better

01:22:58.810 --> 01:23:00.990
in math than female
plants there.

01:23:00.990 --> 01:23:03.830
And so we've got a
genetic trait here

01:23:03.830 --> 01:23:08.100
being a function of whether
or not you get a Y chromosome.

01:23:08.100 --> 01:23:12.560
But then, a few years ago there
was an astonishingly important

01:23:12.560 --> 01:23:14.710
paper published in "Science."

01:23:14.710 --> 01:23:17.940
And what these people did
was look at math performance

01:23:17.940 --> 01:23:22.960
scores-- of I think it was
480,000 different high school

01:23:22.960 --> 01:23:24.130
kids.

01:23:24.130 --> 01:23:27.240
And all over the world.

01:23:27.240 --> 01:23:29.010
They didn't just
study it in America.

01:23:29.010 --> 01:23:32.740
They studied it in 40
different countries.

01:23:32.740 --> 01:23:35.340
And they asked a
very simple question.

01:23:35.340 --> 01:23:40.440
Which is, are there big
differences in gender quality

01:23:40.440 --> 01:23:42.630
of life issues in this country?

01:23:42.630 --> 01:23:47.370
And there is a whole index that
comes out of the World Health

01:23:47.370 --> 01:23:50.750
UN something or other called
a gender equality index.

01:23:50.750 --> 01:23:53.422
Which takes into account,
like, if there is--

01:23:53.422 --> 01:23:55.670
and if there is, how
dramatic of-- a gender

01:23:55.670 --> 01:23:59.010
difference in educational
opportunities,

01:23:59.010 --> 01:24:02.500
in freedom of movement, in
freedom to serve in an elected

01:24:02.500 --> 01:24:06.170
office, and freedom to vote,
in freedom to choose who you're

01:24:06.170 --> 01:24:10.180
married to, and obviously
the enormous variability

01:24:10.180 --> 01:24:12.250
on this planet in terms of that.

01:24:12.250 --> 01:24:17.390
And what they showed was,
the greater the inadequacies,

01:24:17.390 --> 01:24:20.590
the greater the difference
in gender treatment

01:24:20.590 --> 01:24:23.470
in the society across
40 different countries,

01:24:23.470 --> 01:24:27.790
the bigger the difference
there was in math scores.

01:24:27.790 --> 01:24:29.940
It's not a function
of gender, it's

01:24:29.940 --> 01:24:33.260
which society you're
growing up with your gender.

01:24:33.260 --> 01:24:34.660
What was at the most extreme?

01:24:34.660 --> 01:24:36.810
Let me make sure I get
the countries right here.

01:24:36.810 --> 01:24:39.450
Who had the worst profiles
of the 40 countries

01:24:39.450 --> 01:24:42.710
in terms of the biggest gender
differences in these quality

01:24:42.710 --> 01:24:43.920
of life measures?

01:24:43.920 --> 01:24:47.290
Turkey, Tunisia,
and South Korea.

01:24:47.290 --> 01:24:48.890
Where was the United States?

01:24:48.890 --> 01:24:50.420
Sitting somewhere
around the middle

01:24:50.420 --> 01:24:52.440
with most Western
European countries.

01:24:52.440 --> 01:24:55.050
And which were the countries
on earth which, as a block,

01:24:55.050 --> 01:24:58.620
had the lowest degree of
different treatment of people

01:24:58.620 --> 01:25:00.570
in their society
based on gender?

01:25:00.570 --> 01:25:04.830
The ever handy wonderful
Utopian Scandinavians.

01:25:04.830 --> 01:25:06.610
So in comes the Scandinavians.

01:25:06.610 --> 01:25:08.440
And what you show
is, by the time

01:25:08.440 --> 01:25:11.900
you look at the country on
Earth that has the least gender

01:25:11.900 --> 01:25:14.960
differentiation of
any, which is Iceland,

01:25:14.960 --> 01:25:16.910
you notice something different.

01:25:16.910 --> 01:25:19.310
There still is a
gender difference.

01:25:19.310 --> 01:25:24.710
In Iceland, girls are better
at math than boys, slightly.

01:25:24.710 --> 01:25:27.090
A small difference
going on there.

01:25:27.090 --> 01:25:30.320
But nonetheless, as you go
from the countries in which

01:25:30.320 --> 01:25:33.720
from day one, girls
transitioning into women

01:25:33.720 --> 01:25:35.990
are given the most
constraints of freedom

01:25:35.990 --> 01:25:39.170
of life, that's where you're
going to see the biggest math

01:25:39.170 --> 01:25:40.510
difference scores.

01:25:40.510 --> 01:25:44.060
And you look at less and less
of those sort of inequities.

01:25:44.060 --> 01:25:46.980
And the gender difference
in the math score,

01:25:46.980 --> 01:25:49.290
by the time it's at the
Scandinavian countries,

01:25:49.290 --> 01:25:50.460
it's down to zero.

01:25:50.460 --> 01:25:53.260
And then you get to Iceland,
and it actually reverses.

01:25:53.260 --> 01:25:56.800
It's got nothing to do
with your Y chromosome.

01:25:56.800 --> 01:25:58.770
We immediately come
back to the first

01:25:58.770 --> 01:26:02.610
of those questions from before,
that diagnostic question.

01:26:02.610 --> 01:26:03.880
You've got a choice.

01:26:03.880 --> 01:26:07.590
You want to have a sense of,
in this population-- nah,

01:26:07.590 --> 01:26:08.927
even at the individual level.

01:26:08.927 --> 01:26:09.760
You've got a choice.

01:26:09.760 --> 01:26:11.690
You're comparing
two individuals,

01:26:11.690 --> 01:26:14.410
and you want to
guess which one is

01:26:14.410 --> 01:26:16.140
better at math than the other.

01:26:16.140 --> 01:26:19.310
You can either
know their gender,

01:26:19.310 --> 01:26:23.530
or you could know whether they
grew up in Tunisia or Iceland.

01:26:23.530 --> 01:26:25.380
Which fact do you want to know?

01:26:25.380 --> 01:26:27.120
You want to know
about environment.

01:26:27.120 --> 01:26:31.090
Environment is vastly
more powerful there.

01:26:31.090 --> 01:26:33.520
Another feature of that
that has been interesting.

01:26:33.520 --> 01:26:35.700
So you then say
OK, the extremes.

01:26:35.700 --> 01:26:39.300
OK, so in some societies, the
means are exactly the same.

01:26:39.300 --> 01:26:42.180
But what about that difference
way out at the highest

01:26:42.180 --> 01:26:43.390
level of performance.

01:26:43.390 --> 01:26:46.010
As I mentioned the other
day, in the mid-1980s,

01:26:46.010 --> 01:26:48.930
looking at the highest first
percentile of math performance

01:26:48.930 --> 01:26:51.130
on junior high school
kids with their SATs,

01:26:51.130 --> 01:26:55.750
and there was a 13:1 ratio
of males to females in there.

01:26:55.750 --> 01:26:58.540
When it was last
studied a few years ago,

01:26:58.540 --> 01:27:01.550
it's down to a 3:1 ratio.

01:27:01.550 --> 01:27:04.800
Oh, that's obviously due to
evolution over the last 20

01:27:04.800 --> 01:27:07.420
years, because it's
got to be due to genes.

01:27:07.420 --> 01:27:12.530
That's like saying genes explain
the fact that in 1980s people,

01:27:12.530 --> 01:27:15.630
like, wore pads
on their shoulders

01:27:15.630 --> 01:27:19.040
and, like, power sneakers
to work or whatever.

01:27:19.040 --> 01:27:21.120
And the fact that
nobody does that anymore

01:27:21.120 --> 01:27:26.800
shows that the gene for wearing
that on your woman executive

01:27:26.800 --> 01:27:29.980
decor deal has evolved.

01:27:29.980 --> 01:27:31.550
That's asinine.

01:27:31.550 --> 01:27:35.520
You do not go from 13:1
to 3:1 with a trait

01:27:35.520 --> 01:27:38.610
in 20 years in a
highly interbreeding

01:27:38.610 --> 01:27:40.830
mixed population-- in
other words, humans--

01:27:40.830 --> 01:27:42.760
and have this as
a genetic trait.

01:27:42.760 --> 01:27:45.750
Even function at the
extreme has squat

01:27:45.750 --> 01:27:49.130
to do with the
genetics of gender.

01:27:49.130 --> 01:27:52.420
It's, I want to know what
society the person got

01:27:52.420 --> 01:27:53.200
raised in.

01:27:53.200 --> 01:27:55.770
I could care less what
their chromosome is.

01:27:55.770 --> 01:27:57.510
If I want to know
how good they're

01:27:57.510 --> 01:28:00.350
likely to be at math
compared to the other person,

01:28:00.350 --> 01:28:02.250
tell me where they grew up.

01:28:02.250 --> 01:28:05.050
That's the most
important thing to know.

01:28:05.050 --> 01:28:06.700
Interesting additional thing.

01:28:06.700 --> 01:28:10.260
The second most reliable
finding in all of measures

01:28:10.260 --> 01:28:13.330
of cognitive aptitude thing
that has a gender difference

01:28:13.330 --> 01:28:18.340
is, on the average, girls being
better at verbal performance

01:28:18.340 --> 01:28:19.790
tasks than boys.

01:28:19.790 --> 01:28:22.590
Women than men, all
that sort of thing.

01:28:22.590 --> 01:28:25.530
So what's going on in those
40 different countries there?

01:28:25.530 --> 01:28:30.340
What you wind up seeing is,
it depends on which country

01:28:30.340 --> 01:28:30.840
you're in.

01:28:30.840 --> 01:28:33.580
It depends on that
gender equality index.

01:28:33.580 --> 01:28:36.380
And what you see is, in
the worst countries there,

01:28:36.380 --> 01:28:40.180
by these measures, Tunisia-- who
else was it?-- Tunisia, Turkey,

01:28:40.180 --> 01:28:43.530
and South Korea, what
you see is, yeah,

01:28:43.530 --> 01:28:47.500
women get better scores
on verbal tests than men.

01:28:47.500 --> 01:28:50.170
And as you go to the
more equal places,

01:28:50.170 --> 01:28:53.080
the gender difference increases.

01:28:53.080 --> 01:28:55.610
In other words, you've
got one of these.

01:28:55.610 --> 01:28:58.660
The more gender
equal a society is,

01:28:58.660 --> 01:29:01.920
the less of a sex difference
there is in math capabilities

01:29:01.920 --> 01:29:05.770
and the bigger the advantage
is for females over males

01:29:05.770 --> 01:29:07.690
in verbal performance.

01:29:07.690 --> 01:29:10.450
It's got everything to do
with what society you're in.

01:29:10.450 --> 01:29:14.020
This gender difference in
this realm of cognitive skills

01:29:14.020 --> 01:29:16.020
means next to nothing.

01:29:16.020 --> 01:29:18.004
And if I had any
technological skills--

01:29:18.004 --> 01:29:19.420
I kept saying I
was going to bring

01:29:19.420 --> 01:29:21.300
the figure from this
paper, I'll have

01:29:21.300 --> 01:29:23.580
it posted-- because
this one figure,

01:29:23.580 --> 01:29:25.840
it's across all these--
you just look at it

01:29:25.840 --> 01:29:27.620
and there's the answer.

01:29:27.620 --> 01:29:33.230
It's got nothing to do with the
genetics of gender difference.

01:29:33.230 --> 01:29:38.030
OK, so what else would one
want to emphasize here?

01:29:38.030 --> 01:29:40.860
OK, what else would one
want to emphasize here?

01:29:40.860 --> 01:29:44.500
Which is, this is a total
mess and totally complicated.

01:29:44.500 --> 01:29:47.410
OK what have we gotten to so
far in this field of behavior

01:29:47.410 --> 01:29:48.210
genetics?

01:29:48.210 --> 01:29:49.930
There's all these
different ancient ways

01:29:49.930 --> 01:29:51.252
of inferring something.

01:29:51.252 --> 01:29:53.585
Twins, adoption, there's the
much more modern way, which

01:29:53.585 --> 01:29:55.160
is finding the actual genes.

01:29:55.160 --> 01:29:55.910
That's wonderful.

01:29:55.910 --> 01:29:57.000
That's exciting.

01:29:57.000 --> 01:29:58.970
Nonetheless, over
and over and over,

01:29:58.970 --> 01:30:00.920
an environment
gets understudied.

01:30:00.920 --> 01:30:03.140
Environment is far more
subtle than you think.

01:30:03.140 --> 01:30:05.640
Environment starts earlier
in life than you think.

01:30:05.640 --> 01:30:08.780
And when you do it in a very
formal quantitative way,

01:30:08.780 --> 01:30:11.780
analyzing what genetic
influences are about,

01:30:11.780 --> 01:30:14.330
you discover that
scientists study things

01:30:14.330 --> 01:30:17.310
under circumstances where
you constantly underestimate

01:30:17.310 --> 01:30:18.810
the importance of environment.

01:30:18.810 --> 01:30:20.730
Blah, blah, etc., etc.

01:30:20.730 --> 01:30:22.990
But at the end of
the day, don't genes

01:30:22.990 --> 01:30:24.900
have something to do
with something or other

01:30:24.900 --> 01:30:26.040
going on with this?

01:30:26.040 --> 01:30:31.240
And obviously, obviously they
have some very important roles.

01:30:31.240 --> 01:30:35.800
You have genes that completely
determine aspects of behavior.

01:30:35.800 --> 01:30:39.630
Single genes that completely
determine your intelligence

01:30:39.630 --> 01:30:42.200
if you are a housefly.

01:30:42.200 --> 01:30:44.160
Lots of interesting
studies there showing

01:30:44.160 --> 01:30:47.230
single gene determination,
a lot of these behaviors.

01:30:47.230 --> 01:30:50.740
And it doesn't matter sort of
what the economic opportunities

01:30:50.740 --> 01:30:53.680
are for houseflies in that
country versus humans.

01:30:53.680 --> 01:30:55.760
What you see there
is yeah, there

01:30:55.760 --> 01:30:59.010
are realms of behavioral
biology where genes

01:30:59.010 --> 01:31:01.000
play very, very strong roles.

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:03.010
And we will certainly
see some of them

01:31:03.010 --> 01:31:04.690
in the lectures to come.

01:31:04.690 --> 01:31:07.080
But with two qualifiers.

01:31:07.080 --> 01:31:09.600
The first one we
heard the other day.

01:31:09.600 --> 01:31:13.370
Which is, even when, with all
of these criticisms on board

01:31:13.370 --> 01:31:15.550
and you've got
every critical tool

01:31:15.550 --> 01:31:18.350
to slice up anybody
arguing that here's

01:31:18.350 --> 01:31:21.040
a high heritability important
genetic component, blah, blah,

01:31:21.040 --> 01:31:21.750
etc.

01:31:21.750 --> 01:31:23.860
You've completely
cut it to pieces,

01:31:23.860 --> 01:31:25.970
and there still is
a gene that seems

01:31:25.970 --> 01:31:29.750
to be doing something important
for trait X. What we heard

01:31:29.750 --> 01:31:32.860
about the other day is,
nonetheless, think about

01:31:32.860 --> 01:31:36.670
if there is an indirect genetic
route for getting there.

01:31:36.670 --> 01:31:38.910
Is there a gene
for extroversion?

01:31:38.910 --> 01:31:41.480
Or is there a gene
for your height

01:31:41.480 --> 01:31:43.310
and how people of your
height are treated?

01:31:43.310 --> 01:31:45.910
Is there a gene for
picking at grubs?

01:31:45.910 --> 01:31:49.100
Or is there a gene for if you're
really tall, you pick at grubs

01:31:49.100 --> 01:31:50.640
and people don't
make fun of you.

01:31:50.640 --> 01:31:54.300
Is all of that business about
indirect genetic effects?

01:31:54.300 --> 01:31:58.980
So even when you see
a gene for something,

01:31:58.980 --> 01:32:02.510
you have to begin to ask to
make sure that you are not,

01:32:02.510 --> 01:32:05.110
in fact, looking at
an indirect effect.

01:32:05.110 --> 01:32:06.520
Final qualifier.

01:32:06.520 --> 01:32:09.640
When you look at the
really interesting genes

01:32:09.640 --> 01:32:11.176
in terms of what they do.

01:32:11.176 --> 01:32:12.550
When you look at
some of the ones

01:32:12.550 --> 01:32:14.350
that have the most
to do, say, with what

01:32:14.350 --> 01:32:17.270
differentiates our genome
from the chimp genome.

01:32:17.270 --> 01:32:21.400
When you look at things like
juggling your DNA just when

01:32:21.400 --> 01:32:25.000
you're making new neurons,
what you see over and over is,

01:32:25.000 --> 01:32:28.580
what human genes are
about most dramatically

01:32:28.580 --> 01:32:31.820
is coding for ways in
which you have freedom

01:32:31.820 --> 01:32:33.860
from the effects of genetics.

01:32:33.860 --> 01:32:37.730
And that is going to be a
theme endlessly in the lectures

01:32:37.730 --> 01:32:38.490
to come.

01:32:38.490 --> 01:32:40.150
OK.

01:32:40.150 --> 01:32:43.410
For more, please visit
us at stanford.edu.

